 27 February 1997\n{{WDL|60|29|15|16}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Attilio Lombardo]]<ref group=upper-alpha>Player-Manager</ref>\n|align=left| 13 March 1998\n|align=left| 29 April 1998\n{{WDL|7|2|0|5}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Steve Bruce]]\n|align=left| 30 May 2001\n|align=left| 31 October 2001\n{{WDL|18|11|2|5}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Trevor Francis]]\n|align=left| 30 November 2001\n|align=left| 18 April 2003\n{{WDL|78|28|22|28}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Iain Dowie]]\n|align=left| 22 December 2003\n|align=left| 22 May 2006\n{{WDL|123|50|29|44}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Peter Taylor (footballer born 1953)|Peter Taylor]]\n|align=left|13 June 2006\n|align=left|8 October 2007\n{{WDL|60|21|16|23}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Neil Warnock]]\n|align=left|11 October 2007<br />27 August 2014\n|align=left|2 March 2010<br />27 December 2014\n{{WDL|146|50|45|51}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Paul Hart]]\n|align=left|2 March 2010\n|align=left|3 May 2010\n{{WDL|14|3|6|5}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[George Burley]]\n|align=left|17 June 2010\n|align=left|1 January 2011\n{{WDL|25|7|5|13}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Dougie Freedman]]\n|align=left|11 January 2011\n|align=left|23 October 2012\n{{WDL|90|32|27|31}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Ian Holloway]]\n|align=left|3 November 2012\n|align=left|23 October 2013\n{{WDL|46|14|14|18}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Tony Pulis]]\n|align=left|23 November 2013\n|align=left|14 August 2014\n{{WDL|28|12|5|11}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Alan Pardew]]\n|align=left|2 January 2015\n|align=left|22 December 2016\n{{WDL|87|35|13|39}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Sam Allardyce]]\n|align=left|23 December 2016\n|align=left|23 May 2017\n{{WDL|24|9|3|12}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Frank de Boer]]\n|align=left|26 June 2017\n|align=left|11 September 2017\n{{WDL|5|1|0|4}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Roy Hodgson]]\n|align=left|12 September 2017\n|align=left|''Incumbent''\n{{WDL|113|41|28|44}}\n|}\n\n==Honours and achievements==\n===League===\n* '''[[List of English football champions|English top tier (currently the Premier League)]]'''\n** Highest finish 3rd place: [[1990\u201391 Football League|1990\u201391]]\n* '''[[List of winners of English Football League Championship and predecessors|English second tier (currently the EFL Championship)]]''' \n** '''Champions (2):''' [[1978\u201379 Football League|1978\u201379]], [[1993\u201394 Football League|1993\u201394]]\n** Runners-up (1): [[1968\u201369 Football League|1968\u201369]]\n** '''Play-off winners (4)''': [[1989 Football League play-offs|1988\u201389]], [[1997 Football League play-offs|1996\u201397]], [[2004 Football League play-offs|2003\u201304]], [[2013 Football League play-offs|2012\u201313]]\n** Play-off runners-up (1): [[1996 Football League play-offs|1995\u201396]]\n* '''[[List of winners of English Football League One and predecessors|English third tier (currently EFL League One)]]''' \n** '''Champions (1):''' [[1920\u201321 Football League|1920\u201321]] \n** Runners-up (4): [[1928\u201329 Football League|1928\u201329]] (South), [[1930\u201331 Football League|1930\u201331]] (South), [[1938\u201339 Football League|1938\u201339]] (South), [[1963\u201364 Football League|1963\u201364]] \n* '''[[List of winners of English Football League Two and predecessors|English fourth tier (currently EFL League Two)]]''' \n** Runners-up (1): [[1960\u201361 Football League|1960\u201361]]\n\n===Cup===\n* '''[[FA Cup]]'''\n** Runners-up (2): [[1990 FA Cup Final|1989\u201390]], [[2016 FA Cup Final|2015\u201316]]\n* '''[[Full Members Cup]]'''<ref group=upper-alpha>This was an [[association football]] cup competition held from 1985 to 1992. It was also known under its sponsored names of the '''[[Simod]] Cup''' from 1987 to 1989 and the '''[[Zenith Data Systems]] Cup''' from 1989 to 1992. The competition was created after the [[Heysel Stadium disaster]], when English clubs were banned from [[UEFA#Competitions|European competition]], as an additional competition for clubs in the top two divisions</ref>\n** '''Winners (1):''' [[1991 Full Members Cup Final|1990\u201391]]\n* '''[[FA Youth Cup]]'''\n** '''Winners (2):''' 1976\u201377, 1977\u201378\n** Runners-up (2): 1991\u201392, 1996\u201397\n\n===Wartime===\n* '''[[Football League North and South|South Regional League]]'''\n**'''Champions (1):''' [[1940\u201341 in English football|1940\u201341]]\n*'''[[Wartime League|South League 'D']]'''\n**'''Champions (1):''' [[1939-40 in English football|1939\u201340]]\n\n===Regional===\n* '''[[Southern Football League|Southern Football League Division One]]'''\n**Runners-up (1): [[1913\u201314 Southern Football League|1913\u201314]]\n* '''[[Southern Football League|Southern Football League Division Two]]'''\n**'''Champions (1):''' [[1905\u201306 Southern Football League|1905\u201306]]\n* '''United League'''<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Royals Record|title=United League|url=http://www.royalsrecord.co.uk/cups/united.html|accessdate=31 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412045405/http://www.royalsrecord.co.uk/cups/united.html|archive-date=12 April 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n**'''Champions (1):''' 1906\u201307\n** Runners-up (1): 1905\u201306\n* '''[[Southern Professional Floodlit Cup]]'''\n** Runners-up (1): 1958\u201359\n* '''[[London Challenge Cup]]'''<ref group=upper-alpha>This was a [[association football|football]] tournament organised by the [[London Football Association|London FA]]. The London Challenge Cup was first contested in 1908, and other than during the World Wars, was contested every season until 1974, when the tournament was disbanded.</ref>\n**'''Winners (3):''' 1912\u201313, 1913\u201314, 1920\u201321\n** Runners-up (6): 1919\u201320, 1921\u201322, 1922\u201323, 1931\u201332, 1937\u201338, 1946\u201347\n* '''[[Surrey Senior Cup]]'''<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Surrey FA |title=Saturday Senior Cup Previous Winners |url=http://www.surreyfa.com/previous-winners-and-officials/saturday-senior-cup-previous-winners |accessdate=31 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502232940/http://www.surreyfa.com/previous-winners-and-officials/saturday-senior-cup-previous-winners |archivedate= 2 May 2014 }}</ref>\n**'''Winners (3):''' 1996\u201397, 2000\u201301, 2001\u201302\n\n==In popular culture==\nIn the 1999 [[Michael Winterbottom]] film ''[[Wonderland (1999 film)|Wonderland]]'', the scenes of the character Dan and his son at a football match were filmed at [[Selhurst Park]] during Palace's 1\u20131 draw against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] on 6 February 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/results/1999-02-06|publisher=Statto.com|title=Results saturday 6th February 1999|date=17 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526020629/http://www.statto.com/football/stats/results/1999-02-06|archivedate=26 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the [[Mike Leigh]] play ''[[Abigail's Party]]'', the character Tony mentions that he used to play professionally for Crystal Palace but it \"didn't work out\", something actor [[John Salthouse]] brought to the character in rehearsals based on his own life.<ref name=\"Duvitski 6\"/> Salthouse also incorporated the club into the children's television series he wrote, ''[[Hero to Zero]]'', in which the father of the main character once played for Palace reserves.<ref>{{cite news|last=Maume|first=Chris|title=Owen's method is latest pitch at football's screen test|newspaper=The Independent|page=28|date=26 February 2000}}</ref> In the first series of ''[[Only Fools and Horses]]'' a Crystal Palace scarf could be seen on the coat rack, placed there by producer [[Ray Butt]], even though Rodney's middle name was Charlton, as Del revealed on Rodney's wedding day: their mother was a fan of \"Athletic\" not \"Heston\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Simons|first=Raoul|title=Football Talk|newspaper=The Evening Standard|date=25 May 2006|page=59}}</ref> Headmaster Keith Blackwell, who played Crystal Palace mascot \"Pete the Eagle\" in the late nineties, fronted a series of Coca-Cola advertisements in 1996. Blackwell spoke about his role and the embarrassment it brought to his family, and clips of him in costume were used in the campaign.<ref>{{cite news|last=Earls|first=John|title=Game for a laugh; Soccer club mascots keep thousands of fans entertained at every game by dressing up as lions, dinosaurs \u2013 and even a giant hammer! But what makes them want to face the taunts of cheeky away fans?|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Game+for+a+laugh%3B+Soccer+club+mascots+keep+thousands+of+fans...-a061132570|accessdate=28 June 2013|newspaper=The People|date=19 October 1997|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202223317/http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Game+for+a+laugh%3B+Soccer+club+mascots+keep+thousands+of+fans...-a061132570|archive-date=2 December 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Leach |first=Conrad |title=Mascot men, mascot cats and dogs |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/mascot-men-mascot-cats-and-dogs-1185112.html |accessdate=28 June 2013 |newspaper=The Independent |date=15 November 1998 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131218170439/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/mascot-men-mascot-cats-and-dogs-1185112.html |archivedate=18 December 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nThe 2008 episode of ''[[The IT Crowd]]'', \"[[List of The IT Crowd episodes|Are We Not Men?]]\", used Selhurst Park to film the crowd scenes.\n\nAfter the band [[The Dave Clark Five]] performed \"[[Glad All Over]]\" at Selhurst Park in 1968, the song became synonymous with the team, and the Palace fans sing it at every match.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.croydonadvertiser.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/crystal-palace-fans-sing-glad-433141|title=Why do Crystal Palace fans sing Glad All Over and what are its lyrics?|last=Booker|first=James|date=19 May 2016|work=croydonadvertiser|access-date=20 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171115075645/http://www.croydonadvertiser.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/crystal-palace-fans-sing-glad-433141|archive-date=15 November 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Crystal Palace Women==\n{{details|Crystal Palace F.C. (Women)}} <!-- NOTE: Please make detailed additions to the [[Crystal Palace L.F.C.]] article -->\n[[Crystal Palace F.C. (Women)]] is the women's football club affiliated to Crystal Palace, founded in 1992. They are managed by Dean Davenport. The team play in the FA Women's Premier League South, the third tier of English women's football.<ref name=\"ladies\">{{cite web|title=Crystal Palace Ladies FC|url=http://www.crystalpalaceladiesfc.co.uk/|accessdate=27 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701042343/http://www.crystalpalaceladiesfc.co.uk/|archive-date=1 July 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> They play their home games at the [[Hayes Lane]], Bromley, London.<ref name=\"ladies\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=upper-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n;Bibliography\n*{{cite book|last=King|first=Ian|title=Crystal Palace: The Complete Record 1905\u20132011|publisher=Derby Books Publishing Company Limited|year=2012|isbn=978-1-78091-221-9}}\n* Matthews, Tony (editor). ''We All Follow The Palace''. Juma, 1998. {{ISBN|1-872204-55-4}}\n\n;Citations\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''The Crystal Palace Story'' by Roy Peskett, published by Roy Peskett Publishing Ltd (1969).\n* ''100 Years of Crystal Palace Football Club'' by Rev. Nigel Sands, published by The History Press Ltd, (2005), {{ISBN|978-0-7524-3608-1}}.\n* ''Crystal Palace Football Club'' by Rev. Nigel Sands, published by NPI Media Group, (1999), {{ISBN|978-0-7524-1544-4}}.\n* ''Classic Matches: Crystal Palace FC'' by Rev. Nigel Sands, published by The History Press Ltd, (2002), {{ISBN|978-0-7524-2733-1}}.\n* ''Crystal Palace Miscellany'' by Neil McSteen, published by Legends Publishing, (2009), {{ISBN|978-1-905411-55-9}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Association football|English football|London}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{BBC Football Info|BBClinkname=crystal-palace}}\n* {{official website|http://www.cpfc.co.uk/}}\n* [http://www.cpfc.org/ CPFC BBS online fans forum]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060206043559/http://www.palaceradio.net/ Palace Radio 1278am]\n* [http://www.cpfc86.co.uk/ Unofficial Records Site]\n\n{{Crystal Palace F.C.}}\n{{Crystal Palace F.C. seasons}}\n{{Crystal Palace F.C. matches}}\n{{Premier League}}\n{{Football in London}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crystal Palace F.C. 1905}}\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1905]]\n[[Category:Crystal Palace F.C.| ]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in England]]\n[[Category:Premier League clubs]]\n[[Category:Former English Football League clubs]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in London]]\n[[Category:Southern Football League clubs]]\n[[Category:1905 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Crystal Palace, London]]\n[[Category:Companies that have entered administration in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Liron Mets", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crystal_Palace_F.C."}
{"title_page": "Bukayo Saka", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Bukayo Saka\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| fullname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|2001|9|5}}<ref name=PremProfile>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/49481/Bukayo-Saka/overview |title=Bukayo Saka: Overview |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Ealing]], England\n| height = {{convert|1.78|m|order=flip}}<ref name=PremProfile/>\n| currentclub = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n| clubnumber = 77\n| position = [[Midfielder (association football)|Winger]] / [[Defender (association football)#Full-Back|Full back]] / [[Defender (association football)#Full-Back|Wing Back]]\n| youthyears1 = {{0|0000}}\u20132018\n| youthclubs1 = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n| years1 = 2018\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n| caps1 = 19\n| goals1 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2017\n| nationalteam1 = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 2\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2017\u20132018\n| nationalteam2 = [[England national under-17 football team|England U17]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 9\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2018\u2013\n| nationalteam3 = [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 5\n| nationalgoals3 = 1\n| nationalyears4 = 2018\u20132019\n| nationalteam4 = [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 10\n| nationalgoals4 = 4\n| club-update = 23:53, 7 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 12:45, 17 November 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Bukayo Saka''' (born 5 September 2001) is an English professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder (association football)|winger]], [[Defender (association football)#Full-Back|left back]] or [[Defender (association football)#Full-Back|wing back]] for {{English football updater|Arsenal}} club [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].\n\n==Career==\nSaka was born in [[Ealing]], Greater London and attended [[Greenford High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mylondon.news/sport/football/arsenal-fcs-bukayo-saka-young-15549899 |title=Arsenal FC's Bukayo Saka: The young Ealing-born player making his senior debut |first1=Charles |last1=Watts |first2=Katherine |last2=Clementine |website=MyLondon |publisher=Reach |date=13 December 2018 |accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref> He started his career with [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]'s Hale End academy.<ref name=\"G\">{{cite news |last1=Wheatley |first1=Chris |title=Meet Bukayo Saka: The latest Arsenal academy star making a name for himself |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/meet-bukayo-saka-the-latest-arsenal-academy-star-making-a/1s5io5p2o0qk41kfp30ivme0rh |accessdate=29 November 2018 |work=Goal.com |date=20 November 2018}}</ref> Once he turned 17 years old, Saka was given a professional contract by Arsenal and promoted to the under-23 side.<ref name=\"G\"/>\n\nOn 29 November 2018, Saka made his senior competitive debut for Arsenal in their [[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] match against [[FC Vorskla Poltava|Vorskla Poltava]]. He came on as a 68th minute substitute for [[Aaron Ramsey]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Vorskla vs Arsenal |url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2018/11/29/europe/uefa-cup/fc-vorskla-poltava/arsenal-fc/2909571/ |website=Soccerway}}</ref> On 13 December 2018, Saka made his first full home debut for Arsenal in their [[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] match against [[FK Qarabag]].\n\nOn 1 January 2019, Saka made his debut in the Premier League in a 4\u20131 win against [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] after coming on for [[Alex Iwobi]] in the 83rd minute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/he-is-very-important-for-us-emery-excited-by-sakas-arsenal/nxfi3kd76zop1soq6vivyqf09|title=Arsenal news: Emery excited by Saka's Arsenal debut|website=Goal.com|access-date=14 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 September 2019 he scored and provided two assists as Arsenal won 3\u20130 against [[Eintracht Frankfurt]] in their opening group game of the [[2019\u201320 UEFA Europa League]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49745913|title=Eintracht Frankfurt 0\u20133 Arsenal|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=19 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nSaka was rewarded for his efforts in Germany with his first Premier League start, in a 3\u20132 home win over [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]. He then registered an assist for [[Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang]], setting up the Gunners equalizer in a 1\u20131 draw at [[Old Trafford]] against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].\n \nHe then set up [[Gabriel Martinelli]]\u2019s second goal in the 5\u20135 draw at [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]], before assisting Aubameyang in head coach [[Unai Emery]]\u2019s last match in charge, flicking on a low Martinelli cross to Aubameyang to give Arsenal the lead.\n\nHe then got a goal and assist in Arsenal\u2019s 2\u20132 comeback draw at [[Standard Li\u00e8ge]], first whipping in a wonderful cross for [[Alexandre Lacazette]] before guiding the ball home minutes later.\n\nFollowing injuries to [[Sead Kolasinac]] and [[Kieran Tierney]], Saka began to establish himself as a regular in the Arsenal first team at left-back. On 27 January 2020, he scored the opening goal in Arsenal's 2-1 [[FA Cup]] fourth round victory at [[AFC Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] after finishing a 22-pass move, as well as assisting the second goal, scored by [[Eddie Nketiah]]. The goal was later voted goal of the round by the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51272216|title=FA Cup: Arsenal's Bukayo Saka strike voted goal of the fourth round|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref>s\n\nBukayo along with 6 other players with Nigerian descent was named in Arsenal squad for the Europa League knockout phase <ref>{{cite web |url=https://soccerblitz.com.ng/nigeria/meet-the-7-nigerian-players-named-in-arsenal-europa-league-squad/ |title=Meet the 7 Nigerian players named in Arsenal Europa League squad|publisher=Soccer Blitz |website=soccerblitz |accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter a two-week mid-season break, Saka marked his return to action with a strong display at home to [[Newcastle United]], assisting [[Nicolas Pepe]]`s goal. <ref>https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51431286</ref>He then set up [[Alexandre Lacazette]] for his ninth assist of the season in a 1-0 win at [[Olympiacos]] in the UEFA Europa League. <ref>https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51533308</ref> He then hit double figures for assists that season after crossing in for Nketiah in a thrilling 3-2 home win against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]. <ref>https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51519246</ref> Further strong performances against [[Portsmouth]] and [[West Ham United]] further strengthened his grip in the first team.\n\n==International career==\nBorn in England, Saka is of Nigerian descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/sports/football/arsenal-extend-contracts-of-bukayo-saka-arthur-okonkwo-id8857566.html|title=Bukayo Saka and Arthur Okonkwo get professional contracts at Arsenal|first=Tosin|last=Abayomi|website=Pulse.ng}}</ref> Saka has represented England at [[England national under-16 football team|under-16]], [[England national under-17 football team|under-17]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/under17/season=2018/teams/player=250106939/index.html|title=Bukayo Saka at UEFA U17|publisher=[[UEFA]]|accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref> [[England national under-18 football team|under-18]]<ref name=\"U18\">{{cite web|title=England U18s beat hosts France to seal Limoges title with three wins from three games|url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2018/sep/10/france-england-u18s-report-100918|publisher=The Football Association|date=10 September 2018|accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref> and [[England national under-19 football team|under-19]] level.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/under19/season=2019/teams/player=250106939/index.html|title=Bukayo Saka at UEFA U19|publisher=[[UEFA]]|accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Saka was included in the [[England national under-17 football team|England under-17]] squad as they hosted the [[2018 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2018/may/03/england-u17s-squad-named-for-u17-euro-finals-030518|title=England U17s squad revealed for U17 Euro finals on home turf|publisher=The Football Association|date=3 May 2018|access-date=30 November 2018}}</ref> The hosts were eliminated by the [[Netherlands national under-17 football team|Netherlands]] at the semi-final stage on a penalty shootout although Saka scored his spot kick.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/under17/season=2018/matches/round=2000833/match=2024318/index.html|title=England 0\u20130 Netherlands|publisher=[[UEFA]]|date=17 May 2018|access-date=30 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Saka scored the winner for the [[England national under-18 football team|England under-18 team]] in an away game against [[France national under-18 football team|France]].<ref name=\"U18\"/> In November 2018, Saka received his first call-up to the [[England national under-19 football team|England under-19 team]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2018/nov/09/england-u19s-squad-named-for-euro-qualifiers-091118|title=England U19s squad named as they begin their Euro campaign with qualifiers in Turkey|publisher=The Football Association|date=9 November 2018|access-date=30 November 2018}}</ref> He scored on his debut at that age level in a qualifier against [[Moldova national under-19 football team|Moldova]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/bukayo-saka-scores-england-under-19-debut|title=Bukayo Saka scores on England Under-19 debut|publisher=Arsenal F.C.|date=15 November 2018|access-date=30 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 7 March 2020}}<ref name=\"SW\">{{soccerway|bakayo-sako/496730}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[EFL Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[Arsenal F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Arsenal U23]]\n|[[2018\u201319 EFL Trophy|2018\u201319]]<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n| colspan=\"3\" |\u2014|| colspan=\"2\" |\u2014|| colspan=\"2\" |\u2014||4{{efn|Appearances in [[EFL Trophy]]}}||1||4||1\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n|[[2018\u201319 Premier League|2018\u201319]]<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n|[[Premier League]]||1||0||1||0||0||0||2{{efn|name=UEL|Appearances in [[UEFA Europa League]]}}||0||4||0\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Premier League|2019\u201320]]<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n|Premier League||18||0||3||1||2||0||6{{efn|name=UEL|Appearances in [[UEFA Europa League]]}}||2||29||3\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!19!!0!!4!!1!!2!!0!!12!!3!!37!!4\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Arsenal'''\n*[[UEFA Europa League]] runner-up: [[2018\u201319 UEFA Europa League|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48368406 |title=Chelsea 4\u20131 Arsenal |first=Chris |last=Bevan |work=BBC Sport |date=29 May 2019 |accessdate=29 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Arsenal F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saka, Bukayo}}\n[[Category:2001 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Ealing]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Arsenal F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English people of Nigerian descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Bukayo Saka\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| fullname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|2001|9|5}}<ref name=PremProfile>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/49481/Bukayo-Saka/overview |title=Bukayo Saka: Overview |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Ealing]], England\n| height = {{convert|1.78|m|order=flip}}<ref name=PremProfile/>\n| currentclub = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n| clubnumber = 77\n| position = [[Midfielder (association football)|Winger]] / [[Defender (association football)#Full-Back|Full back]] / [[Defender (association football)#Full-Back|Wing Back]]\n| youthyears1 = {{0|0000}}\u20132018\n| youthclubs1 = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n| years1 = 2018\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n| caps1 = 19\n| goals1 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2017\n| nationalteam1 = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 2\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2017\u20132018\n| nationalteam2 = [[England national under-17 football team|England U17]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 9\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2018\u2013\n| nationalteam3 = [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 5\n| nationalgoals3 = 1\n| nationalyears4 = 2018\u20132019\n| nationalteam4 = [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 10\n| nationalgoals4 = 4\n| club-update = 23:53, 7 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 12:45, 17 November 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Bukayo Saka''' (born 5 September 2001) is an English professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder (association football)|winger]], [[Defender (association football)#Full-Back|left back]] or [[Defender (association football)#Full-Back|wing back]] for {{English football updater|Arsenal}} club [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].\n\n==Career==\nSaka was born in [[Ealing]], Greater London and attended [[Greenford High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mylondon.news/sport/football/arsenal-fcs-bukayo-saka-young-15549899 |title=Arsenal FC's Bukayo Saka: The young Ealing-born player making his senior debut |first1=Charles |last1=Watts |first2=Katherine |last2=Clementine |website=MyLondon |publisher=Reach |date=13 December 2018 |accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref> He started his career with [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]'s Hale End academy.<ref name=\"G\">{{cite news |last1=Wheatley |first1=Chris |title=Meet Bukayo Saka: The latest Arsenal academy star making a name for himself |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/meet-bukayo-saka-the-latest-arsenal-academy-star-making-a/1s5io5p2o0qk41kfp30ivme0rh |accessdate=29 November 2018 |work=Goal.com |date=20 November 2018}}</ref> Once he turned 17 years old, Saka was given a professional contract by Arsenal and promoted to the under-23 side.<ref name=\"G\"/>\n\nOn 29 November 2018, Saka made his senior competitive debut for Arsenal in their [[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] match against [[FC Vorskla Poltava|Vorskla Poltava]]. He came on as a 68th minute substitute for [[Aaron Ramsey]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Vorskla vs Arsenal |url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2018/11/29/europe/uefa-cup/fc-vorskla-poltava/arsenal-fc/2909571/ |website=Soccerway}}</ref> On 13 December 2018, Saka made his first full home debut for Arsenal in their [[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] match against [[FK Qarabag]].\n\nOn 1 January 2019, Saka made his debut in the Premier League in a 4\u20131 win against [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] after coming on for [[Alex Iwobi]] in the 83rd minute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/he-is-very-important-for-us-emery-excited-by-sakas-arsenal/nxfi3kd76zop1soq6vivyqf09|title=Arsenal news: Emery excited by Saka's Arsenal debut|website=Goal.com|access-date=14 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 September 2019 he scored and provided two assists as Arsenal won 3\u20130 against [[Eintracht Frankfurt]] in their opening group game of the [[2019\u201320 UEFA Europa League]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49745913|title=Eintracht Frankfurt 0\u20133 Arsenal|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=19 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nSaka was rewarded for his efforts in Germany with his first Premier League start, in a 3\u20132 home win over [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]. He then registered an assist for [[Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang]], setting up the Gunners equalizer in a 1\u20131 draw at [[Old Trafford]] against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].\n \nHe then set up [[Gabriel Martinelli]]\u2019s second goal in the 5\u20135 draw at [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]], before assisting Aubameyang in head coach [[Unai Emery]]\u2019s last match in charge, flicking on a low Martinelli cross to Aubameyang to give Arsenal the lead.\n\nHe then got a goal and assist in Arsenal\u2019s 2\u20132 comeback draw at [[Standard Li\u00e8ge]], first whipping in a wonderful cross for [[Alexandre Lacazette]] before guiding the ball home minutes later.\n\nFollowing injuries to [[Sead Kolasinac]] and [[Kieran Tierney]], Saka began to establish himself as a regular in the Arsenal first team at left-back. On 27 January 2020, he scored the opening goal in Arsenal's 2-1 [[FA Cup]] fourth round victory at [[AFC Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] after finishing a 22-pass move, as well as assisting the second goal, scored by [[Eddie Nketiah]]. The goal was later voted goal of the round by the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51272216|title=FA Cup: Arsenal's Bukayo Saka strike voted goal of the fourth round|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref>s\n\nBukayo along with 6 other players with Nigerian descent was named in Arsenal squad for the Europa League knockout phase <ref>{{cite web |url=https://soccerblitz.com.ng/nigeria/meet-the-7-nigerian-players-named-in-arsenal-europa-league-squad/ |title=Meet the 7 Nigerian players named in Arsenal Europa League squad|publisher=Soccer Blitz |website=soccerblitz |accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter a two-week mid-season break, Saka marked his return to action with a strong display at home to [[Newcastle United]], assisting [[Nicolas Pepe]]`s goal. <ref>https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51431286</ref>He then set up [[Alexandre Lacazette]] for his ninth assist of the season in a 1-0 win at [[Olympiacos]] in the UEFA Europa League. <ref>https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51533308</ref> He then hit double figures for assists that season after crossing in for Nketiah in a thrilling 3-2 home win against [[Everton]]. <ref>https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51519246</ref> Further strong performances against [[Portsmouth]] and [[West Ham United]] further strengthened his grip in the first team.\n\n==International career==\nBorn in England, Saka is of Nigerian descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/sports/football/arsenal-extend-contracts-of-bukayo-saka-arthur-okonkwo-id8857566.html|title=Bukayo Saka and Arthur Okonkwo get professional contracts at Arsenal|first=Tosin|last=Abayomi|website=Pulse.ng}}</ref> Saka has represented England at [[England national under-16 football team|under-16]], [[England national under-17 football team|under-17]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/under17/season=2018/teams/player=250106939/index.html|title=Bukayo Saka at UEFA U17|publisher=[[UEFA]]|accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref> [[England national under-18 football team|under-18]]<ref name=\"U18\">{{cite web|title=England U18s beat hosts France to seal Limoges title with three wins from three games|url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2018/sep/10/france-england-u18s-report-100918|publisher=The Football Association|date=10 September 2018|accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref> and [[England national under-19 football team|under-19]] level.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/under19/season=2019/teams/player=250106939/index.html|title=Bukayo Saka at UEFA U19|publisher=[[UEFA]]|accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Saka was included in the [[England national under-17 football team|England under-17]] squad as they hosted the [[2018 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2018/may/03/england-u17s-squad-named-for-u17-euro-finals-030518|title=England U17s squad revealed for U17 Euro finals on home turf|publisher=The Football Association|date=3 May 2018|access-date=30 November 2018}}</ref> The hosts were eliminated by the [[Netherlands national under-17 football team|Netherlands]] at the semi-final stage on a penalty shootout although Saka scored his spot kick.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/under17/season=2018/matches/round=2000833/match=2024318/index.html|title=England 0\u20130 Netherlands|publisher=[[UEFA]]|date=17 May 2018|access-date=30 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Saka scored the winner for the [[England national under-18 football team|England under-18 team]] in an away game against [[France national under-18 football team|France]].<ref name=\"U18\"/> In November 2018, Saka received his first call-up to the [[England national under-19 football team|England under-19 team]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2018/nov/09/england-u19s-squad-named-for-euro-qualifiers-091118|title=England U19s squad named as they begin their Euro campaign with qualifiers in Turkey|publisher=The Football Association|date=9 November 2018|access-date=30 November 2018}}</ref> He scored on his debut at that age level in a qualifier against [[Moldova national under-19 football team|Moldova]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/bukayo-saka-scores-england-under-19-debut|title=Bukayo Saka scores on England Under-19 debut|publisher=Arsenal F.C.|date=15 November 2018|access-date=30 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 7 March 2020}}<ref name=\"SW\">{{soccerway|bakayo-sako/496730}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[EFL Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[Arsenal F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Arsenal U23]]\n|[[2018\u201319 EFL Trophy|2018\u201319]]<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n| colspan=\"3\" |\u2014|| colspan=\"2\" |\u2014|| colspan=\"2\" |\u2014||4{{efn|Appearances in [[EFL Trophy]]}}||1||4||1\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n|[[2018\u201319 Premier League|2018\u201319]]<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n|[[Premier League]]||1||0||1||0||0||0||2{{efn|name=UEL|Appearances in [[UEFA Europa League]]}}||0||4||0\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Premier League|2019\u201320]]<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n|Premier League||18||0||3||1||2||0||6{{efn|name=UEL|Appearances in [[UEFA Europa League]]}}||2||29||3\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!19!!0!!4!!1!!2!!0!!12!!3!!37!!4\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Arsenal'''\n*[[UEFA Europa League]] runner-up: [[2018\u201319 UEFA Europa League|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48368406 |title=Chelsea 4\u20131 Arsenal |first=Chris |last=Bevan |work=BBC Sport |date=29 May 2019 |accessdate=29 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Arsenal F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saka, Bukayo}}\n[[Category:2001 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Ealing]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Arsenal F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English people of Nigerian descent]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toEverton(link changed toEverton F.C.) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bukayo_Saka"}
