{"title_page": "MegaFon", "text_new": "{{about|the cellular phone operator|a sound amplification device|megaphone|the Austrian street newspaper|Megaphon}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = MegaFon\n| logo = MegaFon_sign%2Blogo_horiz_green_RU_(RGB).svg\n| type = [[Open joint-stock company|OJSC]]\n| traded_as = {{MCX|MFON}}<br>{{LSE|MFON}}\n| key_people = Gevork Vermishyan, CEO (2018)\n| industry = [[Mobile phone|Mobile]] [[telecommunications]]\n| products = Mobile networks, fixed-line telephony\n| revenue = {{wikidata revenue|revenue|USD}}{{wikidata revenue|revenue|ref}}\n| revenue_year = {{wikidata revenue|revenue|year}}\n| operating_income = {{wikidata revenue|operating_income|USD}}{{wikidata revenue|operating_income|ref}}\n| income_year = {{wikidata revenue|operating_income|year}}\n| net_income = {{wikidata revenue|net_income|USD}}{{wikidata revenue|net_income|ref}}\n| net_income_year = {{wikidata revenue|net_income|year}}\n| assets = {{wikidata revenue|assets|USD}}{{wikidata revenue|assets|ref}}\n| assets_year = {{wikidata revenue|assets|year}}\n| equity = {{wikidata revenue|equity|USD}}{{wikidata revenue|equity|ref}}\n| equity_year = {{wikidata revenue|equity|year}}\n| subsid = [[Synterra Media]]\n| owner = [[USM Holdings|USM Group]] (56.32%)<br>[[Gazprombank]] (18.79%)<br>MICL (3.92%)\n| homepage = [http://english.megafon.ru/ www.megafon.ru]\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|May 2002}}\n| location = [[Moscow]], [[Russia]]\n}}\n'''MegaFon''' ({{lang-ru|\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d}}), previously known as '''North-West GSM''', is the second largest [[mobile phone operator]]<ref name=DEAL>[http://www.kommersant.ru/doc-rss.aspx?DocsID=1375118 \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0435 \u043d\u0435 \u0442\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0439] ''[[Kommersant]]''</ref> and the third largest telecom operator in [[Russia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnews.ru/reviews/new/telekom_2014/review_table/5cd536646dd5b9ce85a8d95109866cdfbc6b57b0/|title=\u041e\u0431\u0437\u043e\u0440: \u0422\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043c 2014, CNews Telecom 2014: \u041a\u0440\u0443\u043f\u043d\u0435\u0439\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043c\u043c\u0443\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|work=CNews.ru|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> It works in the [[GSM]],  [[UMTS]] and [[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]] standard. Its main competitors are [[Mobile TeleSystems]] (MTS), [[Bee Line GSM|VimpelCom]] (Beeline), and [[Tele2 Russia|Tele2]] ([[Rostelecom]]) in the cellular segment, and [[Rostelecom]] and [[Interregional TransitTelekom]] in the fixed-line segment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kommersant.ru/doc/1891474|title=\u042a - \"\u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0430\u044f \u0442\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043a\u0430\" \u043e\u0442\u0447\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> As of June 2012, the company serves 62.1 million subscribers in Russia and 1.6 million in [[Tajikistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acm-consulting.com/data-downloads/cat_view/7-cellular/19-cellular-2012.html|title=Downloads - Cellular Data 2012 - Cellular Data|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> It is headquartered in [[Moscow]].\n\nIn 2002 the company changed its name from ''North-West GSM'' to MegaFon when it acquired several regional companies, becoming the first GSM company in Russia to cover all its territory. The name \"MegaFon\" in [[Russian language|Russian]] is spelled and pronounced exactly like the Russian word for [[megaphone]]; other connotations are ''mega-'' as \"big\" and ''fon'' as \"telephone\".\n\n==History==\nJune 17, 1993, was the registration date of North-West GSM CJSC (Saint Petersburg). Alexander Malyshev became the first General Director. The major international investors included Scandinavian companies [[Sonera]] ([[Finland]]), [[Telia International AB]] ([[Sweden]]) and [[Telenor|Telenor Invest AS]] ([[Norway]]). Telecommunication equipment was supplied by [[Nokia]].<ref>[http://www.vsluh.ru/news/economics/144763.html \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u043e\u0442\u043c\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043b \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0435 15-\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0435 \u0432 \u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0435\"]</ref><ref>[http://www.comnews.ru/standart/article/52121 \"\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0437\u0430\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044f\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u044c\"] ''[[ComNews]]''</ref>\n\n1994 \u2013 launch of commercial operation of [[GSM]] ([[2G]]) network, the first in Russia.<ref>[http://www.kommersant.ru/doc/1763459/print \"1993-1994. \u041a\u0430\u043a \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u0430\u0448\u0435 \u0434\u0435\u043b\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0432\u043b\u0438\u044f\u043b\u0430 \u0441\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0437\u044c?\"] ''[[Kommersant]]''</ref><ref>[http://www.brandpedia.ru/index.php?name=Encyclopedia&op=content&tid=546 \"\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0431\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0430 \u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\"] ''[[Brandpedia]]''</ref>\n\n1999 \u2013 number of the company's subscribers became over 100,000. By that time the network of the North-West GSM had completely covered [[Saint Petersburg]] and [[Leningrad Oblast|Leningrad region]], it was also actively expanding in the northern areas of the Russian North-West.<ref>[http://scripts.online.ru/misc/news/00/04/19_094.htm \"\u041f\u043e \u0438\u0442\u043e\u0433\u0430\u043c 1999 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0430\u0431\u043e\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0431\u0430\u0437\u0430 \u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e GSM \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e 140 \u0442\u044b\u0441\u044f\u0447 \u0447\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043a.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20120713102953/http://scripts.online.ru/misc/news/00/04/19_094.htm |date=2012-07-13 }}</ref>\n\nJuly 1999 \u2013 North-West GSM was the first Russian operator that signed [[roaming]] agreements with all countries in Europe. The same year, for the first time ever in Russia, mobile communication started to operate in Saint Petersburg metro, and the operator's spectrum of value-added services included [[Wireless Application Protocol|WAP]]-access to the Internet.\n\n2000 \u2013 shareholders of the company adopted a new strategy that was targeted at the mass market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.algonet.ru/?ID=13180|title=\u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u0434\u0438\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u0430\u043a\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0440\u044b \"\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e GSM\" \u043e\u0434\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043f\u043b\u0430\u043d \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0438\u044f \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.comnews.ru/node/1269 \"\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 GSM\" \u043e\u0431\u0440\u0435\u043b \u0444\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c\"] ''[[ComNews]]''</ref>\n\nNovember 2001 \u2013 number of North-West GSM subscribers exceeded 500,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2001/12/10/59720/|title=\u041a\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0430\u0431\u043e\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432 \"\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e GSM\" \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0432\u044b\u0441\u0438\u043b\u043e 600 \u0442\u044b\u0441. \u0447\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043a.|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2001/12/27/35096/|title=\"\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 GSM\" \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u0438\u043b \u043a \u0440\u0435\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430 \u0441\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0437\u0438 \u0432 \u0422\u0430\u0434\u0436\u0438\u043a\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0435 - \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u044b\u0435 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 - \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430 - \u0424\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0430.\u0420\u0443|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nMay 2002 \u2013 The number of North-West GSM subscribers exceeded  1 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2002/05/06/38455/|title=\u041a \u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438 \"\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e GSM\" \u043f\u043e\u0434\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0447\u0438\u043b\u0441\u044f \u043c\u0438\u043b\u043b\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0430\u0431\u043e\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0442 - \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u044b\u0435 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 - \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430 - \u0424\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0430.\u0420\u0443|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nMay 7, 2002 \u2013 in the course of rebranding North-West GSM CJSC was renamed to MegaFon OJSC. Rebranding of the company was started on April 28, 2002, by change of the logo. At that moment, North-West GSM was merged with Sonic Duo CJSC ([[Moscow]]), Ural GSM CJSC ([[Yekaterinburg]]), Mobicom-Kavkaz CJSC ([[Krasnodar]]), Mobicom-Center CJSC, Mobicom-Novosibirsk CJSC, Mobicom-Khabarovsk CJSC, MCS-Povolzhie OJSC, Volzhsky GSM ([[Saransk]], [[Republic of Mordovia]]).<ref>[http://www.rustele.com/company-profiles/ojsc-megafon.html \"OJSC MegaFon Company Profile on Rustelecom\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314112431/http://www.rustele.com/company-profiles/ojsc-megafon.html |date=2013-03-14 }} ''[[Rustelecom]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.algonet.ru/?ID=12708|title=\"\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 GSM\" \u0432\u043d\u0435\u0434\u0440\u0438\u043b WAP-\u0442\u0435\u0445\u043d\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u044e|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2002/01/18/60424/|title=\"\u0421\u0415\u0412\u0415\u0420\u041e-\u0417\u0410\u041f\u0410\u0414\u041d\u042b\u0419 GSM\" \u0423\u041d\u0418\u0427\u0422\u041e\u0416\u0418\u0422 \u0421\u0412\u041e\u0419 \u041b\u041e\u0413\u041e\u0422\u0418\u041f \u0418 \u041d\u0410\u0417\u0412\u0410\u041d\u0418\u0415|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2002/01/14/35437/|title=\u0417\u0410\u041e \"\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 GSM\" \u0438\u0437\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043b\u043e \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0443 \u0441\u043e\u0431\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 - \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u044b\u0435 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 - \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430 - \u0424\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0430.\u0420\u0443|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stockmap.ru/news/051036330/|title=\u0417\u0410\u041e \"\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 GSM\" \u0438\u0437\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043b\u043e \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u044e\u0440\u0438\u0434\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0443\u0441 \u0438 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043e \u043e\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430 \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\".|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn October 2, 2008, MegaFon launched for operation the first Russian fragment of the third generation network in [[IMT-2000]]/[[UMTS]] ([[3G]]) at the territory of [[Saint Petersburg]] and [[Leningrad Oblast|Leningrad region]]. For the first time ever in this country the radio access sub-system [[UTRAN]] (UMTS Terrestrial Radio Access Network) was launched for trial commercial operation and included 30 base stations. And already on October 24, 2007, MegaFon announced about start of [[3G]] service in Saint Petersburg and Leningrad region. For the first time in Russia, the following services became available for mass users: Internet access at the data transmission speed that is ten times higher than in the existing [[GSM]] networks ([[2G]] and [[2G#Evolution|2,5G]]) of [[GPRS]]/[[EDGE]] technology, high-quality Mobile TV, video communication.<ref>[http://www.cnews.ru/news/top/indexEn.shtml?2007/10/03/268832 \"MegaFon builds up first 3G network fragment in Russia\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140811170404/http://www.cnews.ru/news/top/indexEn.shtml?2007%2F10%2F03%2F268832 |date=2014-08-11 }} ''[[CNews]]''</ref><ref>[http://english.pravda.ru/business/companies/04-10-2007/98164-megafon_3g_network-0/ \"Megafon launches first 3G network in Russia\"] ''[[Pravda.ru]]''</ref>\n\nDecember 2008 \u2013 the extraordinary General Shareholders Meeting of MegaFon took a resolution on reorganization of MegaFon OJSC in the form of its merger with Sonic Duo CJSC ([[Moscow]]), Ural GSM CJSC ([[Yekaterinburg]]), Mobicom-Kavkaz CJSC ([[Krasnodar]]), Mobicom-Center CJSC, Mobicom-Novosibirsk CJSC, Mobicom-Khabarovsk CJSC, MCS-Povolzhie OJSC. The number of subscribers exceeded 43.2 million.<ref>[http://www.comnews.ru/node/19796 \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0441\u044f \u043a \u0440\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\"] ''[[ComNews]]''</ref><ref>[http://www.sotovik.ru/news/megafon-gotovitsia-k-reorganizacsii.html \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0441\u044f \u043a \u0440\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\"] ''[[Sotovik]]''</ref>\n\nOn March 16, 2009, MegaFon founded a virtual mobile network operator \"PROSTO\" (Just for Communication) on the basis of the Stolichny Branch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rb.ru/article/megafon-sozdaet-diskauntera-prosto-dlya-obshheniya/5719657.html|title=\"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u0441\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0434\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0443\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0430 \"\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f\"|work=RB.ru - \u0411\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0435\u0441 \u0438\u0437\u043d\u0443\u0442\u0440\u0438, \u041a\u0430\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0440\u0430, \u041e\u0444\u0438\u0441\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0436\u0438\u0437\u043d\u044c|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://kommersant.ru/doc/1489975 \"\u0423 \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\u0430\" \u0432\u0441\u0435 \u043d\u0435 \"\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\"] ''[[Kommersant]]''</ref><ref>[http://www.mobile-review.com/articles/2009/mega-prosto-mvno.shtml \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d \u00ab\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u00bb: \u0447\u0435\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0442\u044b\u0439 \u043d\u0435 \u043b\u0438\u0448\u043d\u0438\u0439, \u0447\u0435\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0442\u044b\u0439 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0439?\"] ''[[Mobile-review.com]]''</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2009, reorganization was completed, and now mobile communication services in Russia are provided by the North-West, Stolichny, Kavkaz, Center, Volga, Ural, Siberia and Far East branches of MegaFon OJSC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tssonline.ru/newstext.php?news_id=59255|title=\"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u0437\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0448\u0438\u043b \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0446\u0435\u0441\u0441 \u0440\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.vsluh.ru/news/economics/174696.html \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d \u0440\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0441\u044f\"]</ref>\n\nOn September 25, 2009, it was announced about rebranding of TT mobile CJSC, subsidiary of MegaFon that provided telecom services under the brand of MLT \u2013 \"Mobile Lines of Tajikistan\". The new company's name is MegaFon-Tajikistan.<ref name=\"telecompaper.com\">[http://www.telecompaper.com/news/megafon-rebrands-mlt-as-megafon-tajikistan \"Megafon rebrands MLT as Megafon Tajikistan\"] ''Telecompaper''</ref><ref name=\"researchandmarkets.com\">[http://www.researchandmarkets.com/research/4e80f2/kazakhstan_and_cen \"Kazakhstan and Central Asia Telecommunications Report Q4 2011\"] ''[[Research and Markets]]''</ref><ref name=\"Tajiks say no\u2019 to Megafon brand\">[http://www.telegeography.com/products/commsupdate/articles/2007/03/12/tajiks-say-no-to-megafon-brand/ \"Tajiks say \u2018no\u2019 to Megafon brand\"] ''[[TeleGeography]]''</ref>\n\nSince March 1, 2010, Ostelecom CJSC started to provide telecom services in the Tskhinvali region ([[Occupied territories of Georgia|occupied territory of Georgia]]) under MegaFon brand.<ref>[http://www.telegeography.com/products/commsupdate/articles/2011/09/28/russia-inks-telecoms-cooperation-pact-with-south-ossetia-megafon-launches-3g-through-ostelekom/ \"Russia inks telecoms cooperation pact with South Ossetia; MegaFon launches 3G through Ostelekom\"] ''[[TeleGeography]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://iwpr.net/report-news/south-ossetia-gets-connected|title=South Ossetia Gets Connected|work=Institute for War and Peace Reporting|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://justamp.blogspot.com/2011/09/megafon-opened-network-3g-south-ossetia.html|title=Just Another Mobile Phone Blog|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.cnews.ru/news/line/index.shtml?2011/09/21/456303 \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043b 3G \u0432 \u042e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0438\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111120030949/http://www.cnews.ru/news/line/index.shtml?2011%2F09%2F21%2F456303 |date=2011-11-20 }} ''[[CNews]]''</ref>\n\nIn June 2010, MegaFon acquired 100% shares of [[Synterra Media|Synterra company]], which was a move to strengthen network infrastructure and enhance the positions in the markets of long-distance communication, fixed and mobile broadband access to the Internet, as well as convergence services.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/02/26/idUSLDE61P26020100226 \"MegaFon buys Russian operator for $710 mln -source\"] ''[[Reuters]]''</ref><ref>[http://rusmergers.com/en/main/395-megafon-pokupaet-sinterru.html \"MegaFon\" buy \"Synterra\"]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''''</ref>\n\nThree months later, the extraordinary General Shareholders Meeting of MegaFon unanimously approved acquisition of 100% shares of PeterStar CJSC from [[Synterra Media|Synterra]].<ref>[http://www.telegeography.com/products/commsupdate/articles/2010/08/25/megafon-consolidating-peterstar/ \"MegaFon consolidating PeterStar\"] ''[[TeleGeography]]''</ref><ref>[http://rusmergers.com/en/mna/4106-.html \"Synterra\" went to MegaFon\"]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://financial.tmcnet.com/expense-management/news/2010/08/24/4971391.htm|title=MegaFon set on PeterStar buy to consolidate northwest ops|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nBased on the results of Q3 2010 MegaFon became the second-ranked operator in mobile revenue.<ref>[http://en.rian.ru/business/20101123/161458606.html \"MegaFon boosts Q3 net profit by 23.1 pct to 14 bln rbls\"] ''[[RIA Novosti]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ceeitandtelecom.com/98944/MegaFon-boosts-Q3-net-profit-by-231-to-RUB-14bn.shtml|title=MegaFon boosts Q3 net profit by 23.1% to RUB 14bn|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wirelessfederation.com/news/30673-megafon-q3-revenue-rises-by-23-russia/|title=MegaFon Q3 revenue rises by 23% (Russia)|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://origin-www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=conewsstory&tkr=MFON:RU&sid=aN9JAE04eknA \"MegaFon S.A. 3rd Quarter Results\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721202340/http://origin-www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=conewsstory&tkr=MFON:RU&sid=aN9JAE04eknA |date=2015-07-21 }} ''[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]''</ref>\n\nBased on Q3 2010 results MegaFon became the leader in the revenue share from [[value-added service]]s (VAS) among the Big Three operators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.procontent.ru/news/19351.html|title=\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d: \u0438\u0442\u043e\u0433\u0438 2010 - \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u0432\u044b\u0440\u0443\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u0438 \u0434\u043e\u043b\u0438 VAS-\u0443\u0441\u043b\u0443\u0433|date=10 March 2011|work=procontent.ru|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.content-review.com/articles/17201/|title=\u0424\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u043e\u0442\u0447\u0435\u0442 \u00ab\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\u0430\u00bb \u0437\u0430 III \u043a\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043b 2011 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 (\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u044f)|date=15 November 2011|work=Content-Review.com|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of 2010, MegaFon became the Top 2 operator (after [[Mobile TeleSystems|MTS]]) in number subscribers among the Russian cellular communication providers.<ref>[http://lenta.ru/news/2010/05/25/phone/ \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0444\u043e\u043d\" \u0437\u0430\u043d\u044f\u043b \u0432\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0435 \u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e \u0432 \"\u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u043e\u0439 \u0442\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043a\u0435\" \u043e\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432\"] ''[[Lenta.ru]]''</ref><ref>[http://www.telegeography.com/products/commsupdate/articles/2011/03/11/megafon-sees-fy10-revenues-increase-18-5-to-rub215-5-billion/ \"MegaFon sees FY10 revenues increase 18.5% to RUB215.5 billion\"] ''[[TeleGeography]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.akm.ru/rus/comments/2010/may/25/ns_12223.htm|title=\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0444\u043e\u043d \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0433\u043d\u0430\u043b \u0412\u044b\u043c\u043f\u0435\u043b\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043f\u043e \u043a\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0443 \u043e\u0431\u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0438\u0432\u0430\u0435\u043c\u044b\u0445 \u0430\u0431\u043e\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.finmarket.ru/z/nws/hotnews.asp?id=1506725|title=\u041f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043a\u0438 \u0432 \"\u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u043e\u0439 \u0442\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043a\u0435\"|work=Finmarket.ru|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.business-magazine.ru/news/pub331748/ \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u0432\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0433\u043d\u0430\u043b \"\u0412\u044b\u043c\u043f\u0435\u043b\u041a\u043e\u043c\" \u043f\u043e \u043a\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0443 \u0430\u0431\u043e\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20120721030538/http://www.business-magazine.ru/news/pub331748/ |date=2012-07-21 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnews.ru/news/top/index.shtml?2010/05/25/392789|title=CNews: \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0444\u043e\u043d\" \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0433\u043d\u0430\u043b \"\u0411\u0438\u043b\u0430\u0439\u043d\"|work=CNews.ru|accessdate=17 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721121510/http://www.cnews.ru/news/top/index.shtml?2010%2F05%2F25%2F392789|archivedate=21 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of 2010, MegaFon acquired the Top Second position in terms of revenue among the Russian Big Three operators.<ref>[http://lenta.ru/news/2011/03/10/viruchka/ \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u0437\u0430\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b \u043e \u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e\u0440\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0432\u044b\u0440\u0443\u0447\u043a\u0435 \u0432 2010 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0443\"] ''[[Lenta.ru]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marker.ru/news/3889|title=\"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\": \"\u041c\u044b \u0432\u044b\u0448\u043b\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0435 \u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e \u043f\u043e \u0432\u044b\u0440\u0443\u0447\u043a\u0435 \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438\"|work=\u041c\u0430\u0440\u043a\u0435\u0440|accessdate=17 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721185700/http://marker.ru/news/3889|archivedate=21 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazeta.ru/news/lenta/2010/10/28/n_1564826.shtml|title=\"\u0412\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438\": \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0444\u043e\u043d\" \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0433\u043d\u0430\u043b \"\u0412\u044b\u043c\u043f\u0435\u043b\u043a\u043e\u043c\" \u043f\u043e \u043e\u0431\u044a\u0435\u043c\u0443 \u0432\u044b\u0440\u0443\u0447\u043a\u0438|work=\u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430.Ru|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.vedomosti.ru/newspaper/article/248574/serebro_dlya_megafona \"\u0421\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0440\u043e \u0434\u043b\u044f \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0444\u043e\u043d\u0430\"] ''[[Vedomosti]]''</ref>\n\nOn July 20, 2011, it was announced about rebranding of TT mobile CJSC. MLT brand was renamed to MegaFon-Tajikistan.<ref name=\"telecompaper.com\"/><ref name=\"researchandmarkets.com\"/><ref name=\"Tajiks say no\u2019 to Megafon brand\"/>\n\nIn November 2011, MegaFon signed a partnership agreement with [[Yota|Scartel]] on joint development of the Fourth Generation networks [[3GPP Long Term Evolution|LTE]] (Long Term Evolution) in Russia. As a result, the company got the opportunity to provide [[3GPP Long Term Evolution|LTE]] [[4G]] services using Scartel's equipment. In its turn, Scartel will be able to use MegaFon's infrastructure.<ref>[http://www.telegeography.com/products/commsupdate/articles/2012/02/22/yota-targets-moscow-lte-launch-in-april-megafon-to-piggyback-as-mvno/ \"Yota targets Moscow LTE launch in April; MegaFon to piggyback as MVNO\"] ''[[TeleGeography]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alacrastore.com/research/moodys-global-credit-research-MegaFon_s_Agreement_with_Scartel_on_LTE_Technology_Is_Credit_Positive-PBC_137855|title=MegaFon's Agreement with Scartel on LTE Technology Is Credit Positive|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.telecompaper.com/news/megafon-plans-lte-launch-on-yota-network-in-h1 \"Megafon plans LTE launch on Yota network in H1\"] ''Telecompaper''</ref>\n\nIn December 2011, the company created MegaLabs, 100% subsidiary, which is the single center of design and launch of value-added services.<ref>[http://www.telecompaper.com/news/megafon-to-outsource-vas-to-subsidiary \"Megafon to outsource VAS to subsidiary\"] ''Telecompaper''</ref><ref>[http://www.sotovik.ru/news/megafon-vivodit-megalabs.html \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u0432\u044b\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442 MegaLabs\"] ''[[Sotovik.ru]]''</ref>\n\nIn August 2012 MegaFon released its first smartphone called [[Intel AZ210|Megafon Mint]] in Russia with the new Intel [[Atom (system on chip)]].<ref>[http://newsroom.intel.com/community/intel_newsroom/blog/2012/08/22/megafon-announces-its-first-smartphone-with-intel-inside \"MegaFon Announces its First Smartphone with Intel Inside\u00ae\"] ''[[intel.com]]''</ref> In December 2013 the company received a licence for cable television broadcasting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comnews.ru/node/79814|title=\"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0438\u043b \u043b\u0438\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0437\u0438\u044e \u043d\u0430 \u043a\u0430\u0431\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0432\u0435\u0449\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2014 the company has launched international [[roaming]] data networks in the [[4G|fourth generation]]. The first countries where service is available are [[Switzerland]] and [[South Korea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comnews.ru/node/80393|title=\"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u043e\u0442\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b \u0447\u0435\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0442\u043e\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0437\u0430 \u0440\u0443\u0431\u0435\u0436|work=comnews.ru|date=30 January 2014|accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref> The same month MegaFon CEO Ivan Tavrin obtained a 12% stake of [[VK.com]], Russia's most popular social networking website, from VK's founder [[Pavel Durov]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Usmanov tightens hold on Russian social net VKontakte as founder sells stake|url=http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/business/technology/a/21024349/usmanov-tightens-hold-on-russian-social-net-vkontakte-as-founder-sells-stake/|publisher=The West Australian (Reuters)|accessdate=18 February 2014|author=Maria Kiselyova}}</ref>\n\nOn February 2014 board of directors of MegaFon has approved a deal to buy a 100% voting stake in SMARTS Volgograd, a unit of mobile firm SMARTS which covers the Volga and central regions of the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1prime.biz/news/telecommunications/_Russias_MegaFon_board_approves_buying_SMARTS_Volgograd_unit/0/%7B78A21470-3103-4A69-8D3A-1E982C019F51%7D.uif|title=Russia\u2019s MegaFon board approves buying SMARTS\u2019 Volgograd unit|work=Prime|date=13 February 2014|accessdate=13 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the same month, MegaFon commercially launched fragment network LTE Advanced (LTE-A) within the [[Garden Ring]] in Moscow. Formerly MegaFon network tested LTE-A in the [[2014 Winter Olympics]] in [[Sochi]]. For this Megafon uses bands in the range 2600&nbsp;MHz own unique combination of frequency spectrum and network resource of [[Skartel]] as a mobile virtual network operator ([[MVNO]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comnews.ru/node/80856|title=LTE \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0443\u043b\u043e\u0441\u044c \u0432 \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0435|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Hardware branding==\nIn recent years, the company began production of hardware under \"MegaFon\" brand. These include fixed and mobile phones<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spb.shop.megafon.ru/mobile.html?csi_params=124915|title=\u041c\u043e\u0431\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0444\u043e\u043d\u044b|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> as well as [[tablet computers]] branded as ''MegaFon Login''. They are produced in Taiwan and may bear technical indexes such as \"SP-AI\" and \"MT3A\".<ref>{{in lang|ru}} See Russian article [[:ru:\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d Login]] for details in Russian</ref>\n\n==Owners and management==\nThe Company was founded by the largest foreign investors: [[Sonera]] ([[Finland]]), [[Telia International AB]] ([[Sweden]]) now merged into [[Telia Company]], along with [[Telenor|Telenor Invest AS]] ([[Norway]]). Telecom equipment was purchased from [[Nokia]].\n\nThe owners of the company as of March 2018 are as follows:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://corp.megafon.com/investors/stock_and_capital/shareholder_structure/|title=Shareholder structure|website=Press room and Investor Relations \u2014 PJSC \u201cMegaFon\u201d \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d|access-date=2018-03-24}}</ref>\n*[[USM Holdings|USM Group]] (owner \u2013 [[Alisher Usmanov]]) owns 56.32% shares directly\n*[[Gazprombank|Gazprombank Group]] owns 18.79%.\n*MICL owns 3.92%\n\n==Outside Russia==\n\n===Allegations===\n\nThe [[Georgian National Communications Commission]] (GNCC) has accused the Russian mobile telecommunications company MegaFon of illegal business operations and participation in the military and economic annexation of Georgia.\n\nAccording to the GNCC, \"MegaFon\" has provided unlicensed mobile phone coverage in the conflict zones of Georgia beginning in 2005, in particular \u2013 the South Ossetia region. The company covered mostly the areas of dislocation of the Russian military forces present in Georgia under the CIS peacekeeping mandate. The rest of the area was mostly covered by the Georgian mobile phone carriers \"Geocell\" Ltd. and \"Magticom\". In the spring of 2008, GNCC received complaints from Georgian mobile communication companies regarding the destruction of their communication facilities in the region and installation of MegaFon antennas. The GNCC conducted survey monitoring trips to establish the presence of MegaFon's unlicensed coverage. \nThe GNCC has imposed two fines on MegaFon: the first \u2013 in the amount of 5,000 GEL ($3,750) in July 2008, and the second, for the recurrence of violation in the amount of 500,000 GEL (approx. $350,000) in September 2008.{{Citation needed|date=May 2009}}\n\nBecause Georgian law envisages criminal liability for illegal business activities, the GNCC has notified the General Prosecutor of Georgia on the alleged violations committed by MegaFon. The Prosecutor General of Georgia is expected to initiate criminal proceedings against key officials of MegaFon.\n\nOn October 2, 2008, Tbilisi City Court upheld the decision of GNCC, finding MegaFon liable for providing unlicensed telecommunication services in Georgia.\n\nMegaFon's appeal of the second administrative fine shall be heard by Tbilisi City Court in November 2008.\n\n===Tajikistan===\nMegaFon's only subsidiary outside Russia is [[Tajikistan]]'s [[TT Mobile]].<ref name=DEAL/>\n\n===Uzbekistan===\n''[[Kommersant]]'' reported on September 7, 2006, that MegaFon is negotiating in buying an 85% stake in [[Uzbekistan|Uzbek]] mobile operator [[Coscom]] from the [[MCT Corpation]]. The other 15% stake in Coscom would be held by Coscom management and private shareholders. Analysts estimated Coscom is worth between US$180\u2013200 million. Coscom's has over 300,000 customers.<ref name=DEAL/>\n\n===Iran===\n''[[BBC Persian]]'' reported on May 13, 2008, that Megafon has opened its office in [[Tehran]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/persian/business/story/2008/05/080513_s-iran-megaphone.shtml|title=BBCPersian.com - \u0627\u0642\u062a\u0635\u0627\u062f \u0648 \u0628\u0627\u0632\u0631\u06af\u0627\u0646\u06cc - \u06af\u0634\u0627\u06cc\u0634 \u062f\u0641\u062a\u0631 \u0634\u0631\u06a9\u062a \u0645\u06af\u0627\u0641\u0648\u0646 \u0631\u0648\u0633\u06cc\u0647 \u062f\u0631 \u062a\u0647\u0631\u0627\u0646|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Sponsorship==\n* Megafon is sponsor of [[KHL]]\n* For the [[2009 Formula One season]], MegaFon was one of the sponsors for the [[Renault F1|Renault F1 Team]].\n* Megafon is a national partner for [[2014 Winter Olympics]] in Sochi in 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sochi2014.com/en/team/partners/8650/|title=Olympic Sponsorship - The Olympic Partner (TOP) Programme|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n*MegaFon is a sponsor for Russian e-sports team [[Virtus Pro]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://virtus.pro/en/articles/virtus-pro-declares-partnership-with-megafon|title=Virtus Pro Declares Partnership With MegaFon|publisher=Virtus.pro|accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref>\n*MegaFon sponsor English Premier League team [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]\n\n== Criticism ==\n\nBy November 2012 MegaFon received a number of orders from [[Telecommunications in Russia|Russian telecommunication]] and consumer market authorities to amend contracts with its 63 million subscribers and to make these contracts compliant with requirements of Russian law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsoc.ru/news/rsoc/news14251.htm?print=1|title=\u0420\u0410\u0417\u042a\u042f\u0421\u041d\u0415\u041d\u0418\u0415 \u0420\u041e\u0421\u041a\u041e\u041c\u041d\u0410\u0414\u0417\u041e\u0420\u0410 \u0432 \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0437\u0438 \u0441 \u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f\u043c\u0438 \u0432 \u0421\u041c\u0418 \u043e \u043d\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u041e\u0410\u041e \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u041f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b \u043e\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0443\u0441\u043b\u0443\u0433 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0437\u0438|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> All MegaFon's attempts to challenge these orders in Russian arbitration courts were unsuccessful.<ref>[http://kad.arbitr.ru/Card/818cf984-0543-4a32-bf33-c7c683084c5a Arbitration case \u041063-11458/2010]</ref><ref>[http://kad.arbitr.ru/Card/c56797d4-02c7-49d9-b80a-4ab22ade7fcc Arbitration case \u041037-395/2011]</ref>\n\nMegaFon violated consumer rights a number of times in 2012 calendar year.<ref>[http://kad.arbitr.ru/Card/6d8cfc71-7c28-48fe-8eea-4f0b09932133 Arbitration case A68-1413/2012]</ref><ref>[http://kad.arbitr.ru/Card/330101df-2af5-4db5-8f55-6f9734896aa6 Arbitration case A73-4102/2012]</ref><ref>[http://kad.arbitr.ru/Card/066c87d3-0efa-471a-83d2-0cfd1b76272e Arbitration case A37-2296/2011]</ref> Following the recent changes of Russian law (Article 40 in RF Law on February 7, 1992, year No. 2300-1 \"On Protection of Consumer Rights\"), competent authorities may demand an immediate liquidation of the company.\n\nMegaFon did not meet requirements of Russian legislation and did not report any legally required certificates of compliance to the [[Russian Federal Communications Agency|Federal Communications Agency]] Rossvyaz.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rossvyaz.ru/activity/correlation/certification/registerCertificate/|title=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0430\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0437\u0438 (\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0432\u044f\u0437\u044c) - \u0420\u0435\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0440 \u0437\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0444\u0438\u043a\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u0441\u043e\u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0437\u0438|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://habrahabr.ru/post/147653/#comment_4980857|title=\u041f\u043e\u043f\u044b\u0442\u043a\u0430 #2: \u043c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440 \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0437\u0438 \u0420\u0424 \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u044b \u0445\u0430\u0431\u0440\u0430\u043f\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Spam prevention ==\nIn the \u00abMegafon\u00bb network there are a number of security issues and instruments for [[Spamming|spam]] preventing:\n* automation system for collecting and analysis of claims on the facts of the undesirable [[SMS|SMS messages]] ([[smishing]], mailings, notifications about discounts, sales, etc.). Short number \u00ab1911\u00bb. It is enough to send the received undesirable message to this number;<ref>[http://spb.megafon.ru/bezopasnoe_obschenie/news/20150908-1302.html Amendments to the \"Communications\" law allowed \"MegaFon\" to reduce a number of complaints for spam almost by 9 times] (ru)</ref>\n* it is possible to report about the fraud manually, having filled a form online on the specialized portal \"Safe communications\";<ref>[http://www.stopfraud.megafon.ru www.stopfraud.megafon.ru]</ref>\n* protection against the undesirable entering [[Cold calling|cold calls]], casual <ref>[http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/cold%20call cold call]</ref> (\u0441ell time) calls, [[Voice phishing|vishing]], [[Social engineering (security)#Quid pro quo|Quid pro quo]] <ref>[https://technet.microsoft.com/en-nz/library/cc875841.aspx Telephone-Based Threats]</ref> is paid.<ref name=\"black_list\">[http://spb.megafon.ru/services/calls/chernyjo_spisok.html \u00abBlack list\u00bb]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* [[Helsingin Sanomat]] 28 March 2006 {{in lang|fi}}\n* [http://www.themoscowtimes.com/stories/2005/07/26/001.html Russia at Heart of German Probe] \u2013 [[Moscow Times]] July 26, 2005\n*[http://www.hs.fi/english/article/European+Commission+to+investigate+TeliaSonera+deals+in+Russia/1135219321540 European Commission to investigate TeliaSonera deals in Russia] \u2013 [[Helsingin Sanomat]] 28 March 2006\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040717161625/http://eng.megafon.ru/ MegaFon English corporate site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070930170829/http://www.kommersant.com/p681467/r_500/Alfa_Group_Accused_of_Bribing_to_Buy_MegaFon/ Alfa Group Accused of Bribing to Buy MegaFon] June 13, 2006\n*[https://archive.today/20130104131236/http://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS182230+23-Sep-2008+PRN20080923 Reuters: Georgia's Communications Commission Fines Russia's Megafon; Decries 'Economic Annexation']\n*[https://www.reuters.com/article/marketsNews/idUSMCH62790120080926?sp=true Reuters:Georgia threatens to multiply Russia MegaFon fine]\n*[https://www.reuters.com/article/email/idUSTRE4925D120081003 Reuters: Georgia files charges against Russia's MegaFon]\n*[https://archive.today/20130104130745/http://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS147417+02-Oct-2008+PRN20081002 Reuters: Megafon Goes to Court in Georgia over Disputed South Ossetia Operations]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081028174147/http://www.eurasianet.org/departments/insightb/articles/eav102308b.shtml EurasiaNet: THE FIGHT BETWEEN TBILISI AND MOSCOW OVER SOUTH OSSETIA GOES CELLULAR]\n*[https://archive.today/20130105155236/http://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS177793+16-Dec-2008+PRN20081216 Reuters: Court Upholds Fine Against Megafon for Illegal Operations in Georgia]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/jan/23/russia-alqaida-putin-bin-laden Guardian: Dreams of empire strike back Q: What do Osama bin Laden and Vladimir Putin have in common? A: Worrying ambitions to reverse imperial decline]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110208033744/http://hellomegafon.com/ Unofficial MegaFon page]\n\n{{Russian mobile phone companies}}\n{{Moscow Exchange Index}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Megafon}}\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies of Russia]]\n[[Category:Mobile phone companies of Russia]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Russian brands]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2002]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Moscow Exchange]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the cellular phone operator|a sound amplification device|megaphone|the Austrian street newspaper|Megaphon}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = MegaFon\n| logo = MegaFon_sign%2Blogo_horiz_green_RU_(RGB).svg\n| type = [[Open joint-stock company|OJSC]]\n| traded_as = {{MCX|MFON}}<br>{{LSE|MFON}}\n| key_people = Gevork Vermishyan, CEO (2018)\n| industry = [[Mobile phone|Mobile]] [[telecommunications]]\n| products = Mobile networks, fixed-line telephony\n| revenue = {{wikidata revenue|revenue|USD}}{{wikidata revenue|revenue|ref}}\n| revenue_year = {{wikidata revenue|revenue|year}}\n| operating_income = {{wikidata revenue|operating_income|USD}}{{wikidata revenue|operating_income|ref}}\n| income_year = {{wikidata revenue|operating_income|year}}\n| net_income = {{wikidata revenue|net_income|USD}}{{wikidata revenue|net_income|ref}}\n| net_income_year = {{wikidata revenue|net_income|year}}\n| assets = {{wikidata revenue|assets|USD}}{{wikidata revenue|assets|ref}}\n| assets_year = {{wikidata revenue|assets|year}}\n| equity = {{wikidata revenue|equity|USD}}{{wikidata revenue|equity|ref}}\n| equity_year = {{wikidata revenue|equity|year}}\n| subsid = [[Synterra Media]]\n| owner = [[USM Holdings|USM Group]] (56.32%)<br>[[Gazprombank]] (18.79%)<br>MICL (3.92%)\n| homepage = [http://english.megafon.ru/ www.megafon.ru]\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|May 2002}}\n| location = [[Moscow]], [[Russia]]\n}}\n'''MegaFon''' ({{lang-ru|\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d}}), previously known as '''North-West GSM''', is the second largest [[mobile phone operator]]<ref name=DEAL>[http://www.kommersant.ru/doc-rss.aspx?DocsID=1375118 \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0435 \u043d\u0435 \u0442\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0439] ''[[Kommersant]]''</ref> and the third largest telecom operator in [[Russia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnews.ru/reviews/new/telekom_2014/review_table/5cd536646dd5b9ce85a8d95109866cdfbc6b57b0/|title=\u041e\u0431\u0437\u043e\u0440: \u0422\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043c 2014, CNews Telecom 2014: \u041a\u0440\u0443\u043f\u043d\u0435\u0439\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043c\u043c\u0443\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|work=CNews.ru|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> It works in the [[GSM]],  [[UMTS]] and [[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]] standard. Its main competitors are [[Mobile TeleSystems]] (MTS), [[Bee Line GSM|VimpelCom]] (Beeline), and [[Tele2 Russia|Tele2]] ([[Rostelecom]]) in the cellular segment, and [[Rostelecom]] and [[Interregional TransitTelekom]] in the fixed-line segment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kommersant.ru/doc/1891474|title=\u042a - \"\u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0430\u044f \u0442\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043a\u0430\" \u043e\u0442\u0447\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> As of June 2012, the company serves 62.1 million subscribers in Russia and 1.6 million in [[Tajikistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acm-consulting.com/data-downloads/cat_view/7-cellular/19-cellular-2012.html|title=Downloads - Cellular Data 2012 - Cellular Data|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> It is headquartered in [[Moscow]].\n\nIn 2002 the company changed its name from ''North-West GSM'' to MegaFon when it acquired several regional companies, becoming the first GSM company in Russia to cover all its territory. The name \"MegaFon\" in [[Russian language|Russian]] is spelled and pronounced exactly like the Russian word for [[megaphone]]; other connotations are ''mega-'' as \"big\" and ''fon'' as \"telephone\".\n\n==History==\nJune 17, 1993, was the registration date of North-West GSM CJSC (Saint Petersburg). Alexander Malyshev became the first General Director. The major international investors included Scandinavian companies [[Sonera]] ([[Finland]]), [[Telia International AB]] ([[Sweden]]) and [[Telenor|Telenor Invest AS]] ([[Norway]]). Telecommunication equipment was supplied by [[Nokia]].<ref>[http://www.vsluh.ru/news/economics/144763.html \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u043e\u0442\u043c\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043b \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0435 15-\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0435 \u0432 \u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0435\"]</ref><ref>[http://www.comnews.ru/standart/article/52121 \"\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0437\u0430\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044f\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u044c\"] ''[[ComNews]]''</ref>\n\n1994 \u2013 launch of commercial operation of [[GSM]] ([[2G]]) network, the first in Russia.<ref>[http://www.kommersant.ru/doc/1763459/print \"1993-1994. \u041a\u0430\u043a \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u0430\u0448\u0435 \u0434\u0435\u043b\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0432\u043b\u0438\u044f\u043b\u0430 \u0441\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0437\u044c?\"] ''[[Kommersant]]''</ref><ref>[http://www.brandpedia.ru/index.php?name=Encyclopedia&op=content&tid=546 \"\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0431\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0430 \u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\"] ''[[Brandpedia]]''</ref>\n\n1999 \u2013 number of the company's subscribers became over 100,000. By that time the network of the North-West GSM had completely covered [[Saint Petersburg]] and [[Leningrad Oblast|Leningrad region]], it was also actively expanding in the northern areas of the Russian North-West.<ref>[http://scripts.online.ru/misc/news/00/04/19_094.htm \"\u041f\u043e \u0438\u0442\u043e\u0433\u0430\u043c 1999 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0430\u0431\u043e\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0431\u0430\u0437\u0430 \u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e GSM \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e 140 \u0442\u044b\u0441\u044f\u0447 \u0447\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043a.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20120713102953/http://scripts.online.ru/misc/news/00/04/19_094.htm |date=2012-07-13 }}</ref>\n\nJuly 1999 \u2013 North-West GSM was the first Russian operator that signed [[roaming]] agreements with all countries in Europe. The same year, for the first time ever in Russia, mobile communication started to operate in Saint Petersburg metro, and the operator's spectrum of value-added services included [[Wireless Application Protocol|WAP]]-access to the Internet.\n\n2000 \u2013 shareholders of the company adopted a new strategy that was targeted at the mass market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.algonet.ru/?ID=13180|title=\u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u0434\u0438\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u0430\u043a\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0440\u044b \"\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e GSM\" \u043e\u0434\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043f\u043b\u0430\u043d \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0438\u044f \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.comnews.ru/node/1269 \"\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 GSM\" \u043e\u0431\u0440\u0435\u043b \u0444\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c\"] ''[[ComNews]]''</ref>\n\nNovember 2001 \u2013 number of North-West GSM subscribers exceeded 500,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2001/12/10/59720/|title=\u041a\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0430\u0431\u043e\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432 \"\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e GSM\" \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0432\u044b\u0441\u0438\u043b\u043e 600 \u0442\u044b\u0441. \u0447\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043a.|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2001/12/27/35096/|title=\"\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 GSM\" \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u0438\u043b \u043a \u0440\u0435\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430 \u0441\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0437\u0438 \u0432 \u0422\u0430\u0434\u0436\u0438\u043a\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0435 - \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u044b\u0435 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 - \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430 - \u0424\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0430.\u0420\u0443|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nMay 2002 \u2013 The number of North-West GSM subscribers exceeded  1 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2002/05/06/38455/|title=\u041a \u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438 \"\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e GSM\" \u043f\u043e\u0434\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0447\u0438\u043b\u0441\u044f \u043c\u0438\u043b\u043b\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0430\u0431\u043e\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0442 - \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u044b\u0435 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 - \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430 - \u0424\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0430.\u0420\u0443|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nMay 7, 2002 \u2013 in the course of rebranding North-West GSM CJSC was renamed to MegaFon OJSC. Rebranding of the company was started on April 28, 2002, by change of the logo. At that moment, North-West GSM was merged with Sonic Duo CJSC ([[Moscow]]), Ural GSM CJSC ([[Yekaterinburg]]), Mobicom-Kavkaz CJSC ([[Krasnodar]]), Mobicom-Center CJSC, Mobicom-Novosibirsk CJSC, Mobicom-Khabarovsk CJSC, MCS-Povolzhie OJSC, Volzhsky GSM ([[Saransk]], [[Republic of Mordovia]]).<ref>[http://www.rustele.com/company-profiles/ojsc-megafon.html \"OJSC MegaFon Company Profile on Rustelecom\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314112431/http://www.rustele.com/company-profiles/ojsc-megafon.html |date=2013-03-14 }} ''[[Rustelecom]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.algonet.ru/?ID=12708|title=\"\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 GSM\" \u0432\u043d\u0435\u0434\u0440\u0438\u043b WAP-\u0442\u0435\u0445\u043d\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u044e|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2002/01/18/60424/|title=\"\u0421\u0415\u0412\u0415\u0420\u041e-\u0417\u0410\u041f\u0410\u0414\u041d\u042b\u0419 GSM\" \u0423\u041d\u0418\u0427\u0422\u041e\u0416\u0418\u0422 \u0421\u0412\u041e\u0419 \u041b\u041e\u0413\u041e\u0422\u0418\u041f \u0418 \u041d\u0410\u0417\u0412\u0410\u041d\u0418\u0415|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2002/01/14/35437/|title=\u0417\u0410\u041e \"\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 GSM\" \u0438\u0437\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043b\u043e \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0443 \u0441\u043e\u0431\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 - \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u044b\u0435 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 - \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430 - \u0424\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0430.\u0420\u0443|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stockmap.ru/news/051036330/|title=\u0417\u0410\u041e \"\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 GSM\" \u0438\u0437\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043b\u043e \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u044e\u0440\u0438\u0434\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0443\u0441 \u0438 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043e \u043e\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430 \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\".|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn October 2, 2008, MegaFon launched for operation the first Russian fragment of the third generation network in [[IMT-2000]]/[[UMTS]] ([[3G]]) at the territory of [[Saint Petersburg]] and [[Leningrad Oblast|Leningrad region]]. For the first time ever in this country the radio access sub-system [[UTRAN]] (UMTS Terrestrial Radio Access Network) was launched for trial commercial operation and included 30 base stations. And already on October 24, 2007, MegaFon announced about start of [[3G]] service in Saint Petersburg and Leningrad region. For the first time in Russia, the following services became available for mass users: Internet access at the data transmission speed that is ten times higher than in the existing [[GSM]] networks ([[2G]] and [[2G#Evolution|2,5G]]) of [[GPRS]]/[[EDGE]] technology, high-quality Mobile TV, video communication.<ref>[http://www.cnews.ru/news/top/indexEn.shtml?2007/10/03/268832 \"MegaFon builds up first 3G network fragment in Russia\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140811170404/http://www.cnews.ru/news/top/indexEn.shtml?2007%2F10%2F03%2F268832 |date=2014-08-11 }} ''[[CNews]]''</ref><ref>[http://english.pravda.ru/business/companies/04-10-2007/98164-megafon_3g_network-0/ \"Megafon launches first 3G network in Russia\"] ''[[Pravda.ru]]''</ref>\n\nDecember 2008 \u2013 the extraordinary General Shareholders Meeting of MegaFon took a resolution on reorganization of MegaFon OJSC in the form of its merger with Sonic Duo CJSC ([[Moscow]]), Ural GSM CJSC ([[Yekaterinburg]]), Mobicom-Kavkaz CJSC ([[Krasnodar]]), Mobicom-Center CJSC, Mobicom-Novosibirsk CJSC, Mobicom-Khabarovsk CJSC, MCS-Povolzhie OJSC. The number of subscribers exceeded 43.2 million.<ref>[http://www.comnews.ru/node/19796 \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0441\u044f \u043a \u0440\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\"] ''[[ComNews]]''</ref><ref>[http://www.sotovik.ru/news/megafon-gotovitsia-k-reorganizacsii.html \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0441\u044f \u043a \u0440\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\"] ''[[Sotovik]]''</ref>\n\nOn March 16, 2009, MegaFon founded a virtual mobile network operator \"PROSTO\" (Just for Communication) on the basis of the Stolichny Branch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rb.ru/article/megafon-sozdaet-diskauntera-prosto-dlya-obshheniya/5719657.html|title=\"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u0441\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0434\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0443\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0430 \"\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f\"|work=RB.ru - \u0411\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0435\u0441 \u0438\u0437\u043d\u0443\u0442\u0440\u0438, \u041a\u0430\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0440\u0430, \u041e\u0444\u0438\u0441\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0436\u0438\u0437\u043d\u044c|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://kommersant.ru/doc/1489975 \"\u0423 \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\u0430\" \u0432\u0441\u0435 \u043d\u0435 \"\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\"] ''[[Kommersant]]''</ref><ref>[http://www.mobile-review.com/articles/2009/mega-prosto-mvno.shtml \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d \u00ab\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u00bb: \u0447\u0435\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0442\u044b\u0439 \u043d\u0435 \u043b\u0438\u0448\u043d\u0438\u0439, \u0447\u0435\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0442\u044b\u0439 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0439?\"] ''[[Mobile-review.com]]''</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2009, reorganization was completed, and now mobile communication services in Russia are provided by the North-West, Stolichny, Kavkaz, Center, Volga, Ural, Siberia and Far East branches of MegaFon OJSC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tssonline.ru/newstext.php?news_id=59255|title=\"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u0437\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0448\u0438\u043b \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0446\u0435\u0441\u0441 \u0440\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.vsluh.ru/news/economics/174696.html \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d \u0440\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0441\u044f\"]</ref>\n\nOn September 25, 2009, it was announced about rebranding of TT mobile CJSC, subsidiary of MegaFon that provided telecom services under the brand of MLT \u2013 \"Mobile Lines of Tajikistan\". The new company's name is MegaFon-Tajikistan.<ref name=\"telecompaper.com\">[http://www.telecompaper.com/news/megafon-rebrands-mlt-as-megafon-tajikistan \"Megafon rebrands MLT as Megafon Tajikistan\"] ''Telecompaper''</ref><ref name=\"researchandmarkets.com\">[http://www.researchandmarkets.com/research/4e80f2/kazakhstan_and_cen \"Kazakhstan and Central Asia Telecommunications Report Q4 2011\"] ''[[Research and Markets]]''</ref><ref name=\"Tajiks say no\u2019 to Megafon brand\">[http://www.telegeography.com/products/commsupdate/articles/2007/03/12/tajiks-say-no-to-megafon-brand/ \"Tajiks say \u2018no\u2019 to Megafon brand\"] ''[[TeleGeography]]''</ref>\n\nSince March 1, 2010, Ostelecom CJSC started to provide telecom services in the Tskhinvali region ([[Occupied territories of Georgia|occupied territory of Georgia]]) under MegaFon brand.<ref>[http://www.telegeography.com/products/commsupdate/articles/2011/09/28/russia-inks-telecoms-cooperation-pact-with-south-ossetia-megafon-launches-3g-through-ostelekom/ \"Russia inks telecoms cooperation pact with South Ossetia; MegaFon launches 3G through Ostelekom\"] ''[[TeleGeography]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://iwpr.net/report-news/south-ossetia-gets-connected|title=South Ossetia Gets Connected|work=Institute for War and Peace Reporting|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://justamp.blogspot.com/2011/09/megafon-opened-network-3g-south-ossetia.html|title=Just Another Mobile Phone Blog|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.cnews.ru/news/line/index.shtml?2011/09/21/456303 \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043b 3G \u0432 \u042e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0438\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111120030949/http://www.cnews.ru/news/line/index.shtml?2011%2F09%2F21%2F456303 |date=2011-11-20 }} ''[[CNews]]''</ref>\n\nIn June 2010, MegaFon acquired 100% shares of [[Synterra Media|Synterra company]], which was a move to strengthen network infrastructure and enhance the positions in the markets of long-distance communication, fixed and mobile broadband access to the Internet, as well as convergence services.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/02/26/idUSLDE61P26020100226 \"MegaFon buys Russian operator for $710 mln -source\"] ''[[Reuters]]''</ref><ref>[http://rusmergers.com/en/main/395-megafon-pokupaet-sinterru.html \"MegaFon\" buy \"Synterra\"]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''''</ref>\n\nThree months later, the extraordinary General Shareholders Meeting of MegaFon unanimously approved acquisition of 100% shares of PeterStar CJSC from [[Synterra Media|Synterra]].<ref>[http://www.telegeography.com/products/commsupdate/articles/2010/08/25/megafon-consolidating-peterstar/ \"MegaFon consolidating PeterStar\"] ''[[TeleGeography]]''</ref><ref>[http://rusmergers.com/en/mna/4106-.html \"Synterra\" went to MegaFon\"]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://financial.tmcnet.com/expense-management/news/2010/08/24/4971391.htm|title=MegaFon set on PeterStar buy to consolidate northwest ops|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nBased on the results of Q3 2010 MegaFon became the second-ranked operator in mobile revenue.<ref>[http://en.rian.ru/business/20101123/161458606.html \"MegaFon boosts Q3 net profit by 23.1 pct to 14 bln rbls\"] ''[[RIA Novosti]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ceeitandtelecom.com/98944/MegaFon-boosts-Q3-net-profit-by-231-to-RUB-14bn.shtml|title=MegaFon boosts Q3 net profit by 23.1% to RUB 14bn|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wirelessfederation.com/news/30673-megafon-q3-revenue-rises-by-23-russia/|title=MegaFon Q3 revenue rises by 23% (Russia)|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://origin-www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=conewsstory&tkr=MFON:RU&sid=aN9JAE04eknA \"MegaFon S.A. 3rd Quarter Results\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721202340/http://origin-www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=conewsstory&tkr=MFON:RU&sid=aN9JAE04eknA |date=2015-07-21 }} ''[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]''</ref>\n\nBased on Q3 2010 results MegaFon became the leader in the revenue share from [[value-added service]]s (VAS) among the Big Three operators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.procontent.ru/news/19351.html|title=\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d: \u0438\u0442\u043e\u0433\u0438 2010 - \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u0432\u044b\u0440\u0443\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u0438 \u0434\u043e\u043b\u0438 VAS-\u0443\u0441\u043b\u0443\u0433|date=10 March 2011|work=procontent.ru|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.content-review.com/articles/17201/|title=\u0424\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u043e\u0442\u0447\u0435\u0442 \u00ab\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\u0430\u00bb \u0437\u0430 III \u043a\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043b 2011 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 (\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u044f)|date=15 November 2011|work=Content-Review.com|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of 2010, MegaFon became the Top 2 operator (after [[Mobile TeleSystems|MTS]]) in number subscribers among the Russian cellular communication providers.<ref>[http://lenta.ru/news/2010/05/25/phone/ \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0444\u043e\u043d\" \u0437\u0430\u043d\u044f\u043b \u0432\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0435 \u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e \u0432 \"\u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u043e\u0439 \u0442\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043a\u0435\" \u043e\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432\"] ''[[Lenta.ru]]''</ref><ref>[http://www.telegeography.com/products/commsupdate/articles/2011/03/11/megafon-sees-fy10-revenues-increase-18-5-to-rub215-5-billion/ \"MegaFon sees FY10 revenues increase 18.5% to RUB215.5 billion\"] ''[[TeleGeography]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.akm.ru/rus/comments/2010/may/25/ns_12223.htm|title=\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0444\u043e\u043d \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0433\u043d\u0430\u043b \u0412\u044b\u043c\u043f\u0435\u043b\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043f\u043e \u043a\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0443 \u043e\u0431\u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0438\u0432\u0430\u0435\u043c\u044b\u0445 \u0430\u0431\u043e\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.finmarket.ru/z/nws/hotnews.asp?id=1506725|title=\u041f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043a\u0438 \u0432 \"\u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u043e\u0439 \u0442\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043a\u0435\"|work=Finmarket.ru|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.business-magazine.ru/news/pub331748/ \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u0432\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0433\u043d\u0430\u043b \"\u0412\u044b\u043c\u043f\u0435\u043b\u041a\u043e\u043c\" \u043f\u043e \u043a\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0443 \u0430\u0431\u043e\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20120721030538/http://www.business-magazine.ru/news/pub331748/ |date=2012-07-21 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnews.ru/news/top/index.shtml?2010/05/25/392789|title=CNews: \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0444\u043e\u043d\" \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0433\u043d\u0430\u043b \"\u0411\u0438\u043b\u0430\u0439\u043d\"|work=CNews.ru|accessdate=17 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721121510/http://www.cnews.ru/news/top/index.shtml?2010%2F05%2F25%2F392789|archivedate=21 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of 2010, MegaFon acquired the Top Second position in terms of revenue among the Russian Big Three operators.<ref>[http://lenta.ru/news/2011/03/10/viruchka/ \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u0437\u0430\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b \u043e \u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e\u0440\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0432\u044b\u0440\u0443\u0447\u043a\u0435 \u0432 2010 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0443\"] ''[[Lenta.ru]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marker.ru/news/3889|title=\"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\": \"\u041c\u044b \u0432\u044b\u0448\u043b\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0435 \u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e \u043f\u043e \u0432\u044b\u0440\u0443\u0447\u043a\u0435 \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438\"|work=\u041c\u0430\u0440\u043a\u0435\u0440|accessdate=17 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721185700/http://marker.ru/news/3889|archivedate=21 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazeta.ru/news/lenta/2010/10/28/n_1564826.shtml|title=\"\u0412\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438\": \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0444\u043e\u043d\" \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0433\u043d\u0430\u043b \"\u0412\u044b\u043c\u043f\u0435\u043b\u043a\u043e\u043c\" \u043f\u043e \u043e\u0431\u044a\u0435\u043c\u0443 \u0432\u044b\u0440\u0443\u0447\u043a\u0438|work=\u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430.Ru|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.vedomosti.ru/newspaper/article/248574/serebro_dlya_megafona \"\u0421\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0440\u043e \u0434\u043b\u044f \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0444\u043e\u043d\u0430\"] ''[[Vedomosti]]''</ref>\n\nOn July 20, 2011, it was announced about rebranding of TT mobile CJSC. MLT brand was renamed to MegaFon-Tajikistan.<ref name=\"telecompaper.com\"/><ref name=\"researchandmarkets.com\"/><ref name=\"Tajiks say no\u2019 to Megafon brand\"/>\n\nIn November 2011, MegaFon signed a partnership agreement with [[Yota|Scartel]] on joint development of the Fourth Generation networks [[3GPP Long Term Evolution|LTE]] (Long Term Evolution) in Russia. As a result, the company got the opportunity to provide [[3GPP Long Term Evolution|LTE]] [[4G]] services using Scartel's equipment. In its turn, Scartel will be able to use MegaFon's infrastructure.<ref>[http://www.telegeography.com/products/commsupdate/articles/2012/02/22/yota-targets-moscow-lte-launch-in-april-megafon-to-piggyback-as-mvno/ \"Yota targets Moscow LTE launch in April; MegaFon to piggyback as MVNO\"] ''[[TeleGeography]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alacrastore.com/research/moodys-global-credit-research-MegaFon_s_Agreement_with_Scartel_on_LTE_Technology_Is_Credit_Positive-PBC_137855|title=MegaFon's Agreement with Scartel on LTE Technology Is Credit Positive|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.telecompaper.com/news/megafon-plans-lte-launch-on-yota-network-in-h1 \"Megafon plans LTE launch on Yota network in H1\"] ''Telecompaper''</ref>\n\nIn December 2011, the company created MegaLabs, 100% subsidiary, which is the single center of design and launch of value-added services.<ref>[http://www.telecompaper.com/news/megafon-to-outsource-vas-to-subsidiary \"Megafon to outsource VAS to subsidiary\"] ''Telecompaper''</ref><ref>[http://www.sotovik.ru/news/megafon-vivodit-megalabs.html \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u0432\u044b\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442 MegaLabs\"] ''[[Sotovik.ru]]''</ref>\n\nIn August 2012 MegaFon released its first smartphone called [[Intel AZ210|Megafon Mint]] in Russia with the new Intel [[Atom (system on chip)]].<ref>[http://newsroom.intel.com/community/intel_newsroom/blog/2012/08/22/megafon-announces-its-first-smartphone-with-intel-inside \"MegaFon Announces its First Smartphone with Intel Inside\u00ae\"] ''[[intel.com]]''</ref> In December 2013 the company received a licence for cable television broadcasting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comnews.ru/node/79814|title=\"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0438\u043b \u043b\u0438\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0437\u0438\u044e \u043d\u0430 \u043a\u0430\u0431\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0432\u0435\u0449\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2014 the company has launched international [[roaming]] data networks in the [[4G|fourth generation]]. The first countries where service is available are [[Switzerland]] and [[South Korea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comnews.ru/node/80393|title=\"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u043e\u0442\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b \u0447\u0435\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0442\u043e\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0437\u0430 \u0440\u0443\u0431\u0435\u0436|work=comnews.ru|date=30 January 2014|accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref> The same month MegaFon CEO Ivan Tavrin obtained a 12% stake of [[VK.com]], Russia's most popular social networking website, from VK's founder [[Pavel Durov]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Usmanov tightens hold on Russian social net VKontakte as founder sells stake|url=http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/business/technology/a/21024349/usmanov-tightens-hold-on-russian-social-net-vkontakte-as-founder-sells-stake/|publisher=The West Australian (Reuters)|accessdate=18 February 2014|author=Maria Kiselyova}}</ref>\n\nOn February 2014 board of directors of MegaFon has approved a deal to buy a 100% voting stake in SMARTS Volgograd, a unit of mobile firm SMARTS which covers the Volga and central regions of the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1prime.biz/news/telecommunications/_Russias_MegaFon_board_approves_buying_SMARTS_Volgograd_unit/0/%7B78A21470-3103-4A69-8D3A-1E982C019F51%7D.uif|title=Russia\u2019s MegaFon board approves buying SMARTS\u2019 Volgograd unit|work=Prime|date=13 February 2014|accessdate=13 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the same month, MegaFon commercially launched fragment network LTE Advanced (LTE-A) within the [[Garden Ring]] in Moscow. Formerly MegaFon network tested LTE-A in the [[2014 Winter Olympics]] in [[Sochi]]. For this Megafon uses bands in the range 2600&nbsp;MHz own unique combination of frequency spectrum and network resource of [[Skartel]] as a mobile virtual network operator ([[MVNO]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comnews.ru/node/80856|title=LTE \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0443\u043b\u043e\u0441\u044c \u0432 \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0435|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Hardware branding==\nIn recent years, the company began production of hardware under \"MegaFon\" brand. These include fixed and mobile phones<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spb.shop.megafon.ru/mobile.html?csi_params=124915|title=\u041c\u043e\u0431\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0444\u043e\u043d\u044b|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> as well as [[tablet computers]] branded as ''MegaFon Login''. They are produced in Taiwan and may bear technical indexes such as \"SP-AI\" and \"MT3A\".<ref>{{in lang|ru}} See Russian article [[:ru:\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d Login]] for details in Russian</ref>\n\n==Owners and management==\nThe Company was founded by the largest foreign investors: [[Sonera]] ([[Finland]]), [[Telia International AB]] ([[Sweden]]) now merged into [[Telia Company]], along with [[Telenor|Telenor Invest AS]] ([[Norway]]). Telecom equipment was purchased from [[Nokia]].\n\nThe owners of the company as of March 2018 are as follows:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://corp.megafon.com/investors/stock_and_capital/shareholder_structure/|title=Shareholder structure|website=Press room and Investor Relations \u2014 PJSC \u201cMegaFon\u201d \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d|access-date=2018-03-24}}</ref>\n*[[USM Holdings|USM Group]] (owner \u2013 [[Alisher Usmanov]]) owns 56.32% shares directly\n*[[Gazprombank|Gazprombank Group]] owns 18.79%.\n*MICL owns 3.92%\n\n==Outside Russia==\n\n===Allegations===\n\nThe [[Georgian National Communications Commission]] (GNCC) has accused the Russian mobile telecommunications company MegaFon of illegal business operations and participation in the military and economic annexation of Georgia.\n\nAccording to the GNCC, \"MegaFon\" has provided unlicensed mobile phone coverage in the conflict zones of Georgia beginning in 2005, in particular \u2013 the South Ossetia region. The company covered mostly the areas of dislocation of the Russian military forces present in Georgia under the CIS peacekeeping mandate. The rest of the area was mostly covered by the Georgian mobile phone carriers \"Geocell\" Ltd. and \"Magticom\". In the spring of 2008, GNCC received complaints from Georgian mobile communication companies regarding the destruction of their communication facilities in the region and installation of MegaFon antennas. The GNCC conducted survey monitoring trips to establish the presence of MegaFon's unlicensed coverage. \nThe GNCC has imposed two fines on MegaFon: the first \u2013 in the amount of 5,000 GEL ($3,750) in July 2008, and the second, for the recurrence of violation in the amount of 500,000 GEL (approx. $350,000) in September 2008.{{Citation needed|date=May 2009}}\n\nBecause Georgian law envisages criminal liability for illegal business activities, the GNCC has notified the General Prosecutor of Georgia on the alleged violations committed by MegaFon. The Prosecutor General of Georgia is expected to initiate criminal proceedings against key officials of MegaFon.\n\nOn October 2, 2008, Tbilisi City Court upheld the decision of GNCC, finding MegaFon liable for providing unlicensed telecommunication services in Georgia.\n\nMegaFon's appeal of the second administrative fine shall be heard by Tbilisi City Court in November 2008.\n\n===Tajikistan===\nMegaFon's only subsidiary outside Russia is [[Tajikistan]]'s [[TT Mobile]].<ref name=DEAL/>\n\n===Uzbekistan===\n''[[Kommersant]]'' reported on September 7, 2006, that MegaFon is negotiating in buying an 85% stake in [[Uzbekistan|Uzbek]] mobile operator [[Coscom]] from the [[MCT Corpation]]. The other 15% stake in Coscom would be held by Coscom management and private shareholders. Analysts estimated Coscom is worth between US$180\u2013200 million. Coscom's has over 300,000 customers.<ref name=DEAL/>\n\n===Iran===\n''[[BBC Persian]]'' reported on May 13, 2008, that Megafon has opened its office in [[Tehran]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/persian/business/story/2008/05/080513_s-iran-megaphone.shtml|title=BBCPersian.com - \u0627\u0642\u062a\u0635\u0627\u062f \u0648 \u0628\u0627\u0632\u0631\u06af\u0627\u0646\u06cc - \u06af\u0634\u0627\u06cc\u0634 \u062f\u0641\u062a\u0631 \u0634\u0631\u06a9\u062a \u0645\u06af\u0627\u0641\u0648\u0646 \u0631\u0648\u0633\u06cc\u0647 \u062f\u0631 \u062a\u0647\u0631\u0627\u0646|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Sponsorship==\n* Megafon is sponsor of [[KHL]]\n* For the [[2009 Formula One season]], MegaFon was one of the sponsors for the [[Renault F1|Renault F1 Team]].\n* Megafon is a national partner for [[2014 Winter Olympics]] in Sochi in 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sochi2014.com/en/team/partners/8650/|title=Olympic Sponsorship - The Olympic Partner (TOP) Programme|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n*MegaFon is a sponsor for Russian e-sports team [[Virtus Pro]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://virtus.pro/en/articles/virtus-pro-declares-partnership-with-megafon|title=Virtus Pro Declares Partnership With MegaFon|publisher=Virtus.pro|accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref>\n*MegaFon sponsor English Premier League team [[Everton]]\n\n== Criticism ==\n\nBy November 2012 MegaFon received a number of orders from [[Telecommunications in Russia|Russian telecommunication]] and consumer market authorities to amend contracts with its 63 million subscribers and to make these contracts compliant with requirements of Russian law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsoc.ru/news/rsoc/news14251.htm?print=1|title=\u0420\u0410\u0417\u042a\u042f\u0421\u041d\u0415\u041d\u0418\u0415 \u0420\u041e\u0421\u041a\u041e\u041c\u041d\u0410\u0414\u0417\u041e\u0420\u0410 \u0432 \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0437\u0438 \u0441 \u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f\u043c\u0438 \u0432 \u0421\u041c\u0418 \u043e \u043d\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u041e\u0410\u041e \"\u041c\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0424\u043e\u043d\" \u041f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b \u043e\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0443\u0441\u043b\u0443\u0433 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0437\u0438|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> All MegaFon's attempts to challenge these orders in Russian arbitration courts were unsuccessful.<ref>[http://kad.arbitr.ru/Card/818cf984-0543-4a32-bf33-c7c683084c5a Arbitration case \u041063-11458/2010]</ref><ref>[http://kad.arbitr.ru/Card/c56797d4-02c7-49d9-b80a-4ab22ade7fcc Arbitration case \u041037-395/2011]</ref>\n\nMegaFon violated consumer rights a number of times in 2012 calendar year.<ref>[http://kad.arbitr.ru/Card/6d8cfc71-7c28-48fe-8eea-4f0b09932133 Arbitration case A68-1413/2012]</ref><ref>[http://kad.arbitr.ru/Card/330101df-2af5-4db5-8f55-6f9734896aa6 Arbitration case A73-4102/2012]</ref><ref>[http://kad.arbitr.ru/Card/066c87d3-0efa-471a-83d2-0cfd1b76272e Arbitration case A37-2296/2011]</ref> Following the recent changes of Russian law (Article 40 in RF Law on February 7, 1992, year No. 2300-1 \"On Protection of Consumer Rights\"), competent authorities may demand an immediate liquidation of the company.\n\nMegaFon did not meet requirements of Russian legislation and did not report any legally required certificates of compliance to the [[Russian Federal Communications Agency|Federal Communications Agency]] Rossvyaz.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rossvyaz.ru/activity/correlation/certification/registerCertificate/|title=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0430\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0437\u0438 (\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0432\u044f\u0437\u044c) - \u0420\u0435\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0440 \u0437\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0444\u0438\u043a\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u0441\u043e\u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0437\u0438|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://habrahabr.ru/post/147653/#comment_4980857|title=\u041f\u043e\u043f\u044b\u0442\u043a\u0430 #2: \u043c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440 \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0437\u0438 \u0420\u0424 \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u044b \u0445\u0430\u0431\u0440\u0430\u043f\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Spam prevention ==\nIn the \u00abMegafon\u00bb network there are a number of security issues and instruments for [[Spamming|spam]] preventing:\n* automation system for collecting and analysis of claims on the facts of the undesirable [[SMS|SMS messages]] ([[smishing]], mailings, notifications about discounts, sales, etc.). Short number \u00ab1911\u00bb. It is enough to send the received undesirable message to this number;<ref>[http://spb.megafon.ru/bezopasnoe_obschenie/news/20150908-1302.html Amendments to the \"Communications\" law allowed \"MegaFon\" to reduce a number of complaints for spam almost by 9 times] (ru)</ref>\n* it is possible to report about the fraud manually, having filled a form online on the specialized portal \"Safe communications\";<ref>[http://www.stopfraud.megafon.ru www.stopfraud.megafon.ru]</ref>\n* protection against the undesirable entering [[Cold calling|cold calls]], casual <ref>[http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/cold%20call cold call]</ref> (\u0441ell time) calls, [[Voice phishing|vishing]], [[Social engineering (security)#Quid pro quo|Quid pro quo]] <ref>[https://technet.microsoft.com/en-nz/library/cc875841.aspx Telephone-Based Threats]</ref> is paid.<ref name=\"black_list\">[http://spb.megafon.ru/services/calls/chernyjo_spisok.html \u00abBlack list\u00bb]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* [[Helsingin Sanomat]] 28 March 2006 {{in lang|fi}}\n* [http://www.themoscowtimes.com/stories/2005/07/26/001.html Russia at Heart of German Probe] \u2013 [[Moscow Times]] July 26, 2005\n*[http://www.hs.fi/english/article/European+Commission+to+investigate+TeliaSonera+deals+in+Russia/1135219321540 European Commission to investigate TeliaSonera deals in Russia] \u2013 [[Helsingin Sanomat]] 28 March 2006\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040717161625/http://eng.megafon.ru/ MegaFon English corporate site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070930170829/http://www.kommersant.com/p681467/r_500/Alfa_Group_Accused_of_Bribing_to_Buy_MegaFon/ Alfa Group Accused of Bribing to Buy MegaFon] June 13, 2006\n*[https://archive.today/20130104131236/http://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS182230+23-Sep-2008+PRN20080923 Reuters: Georgia's Communications Commission Fines Russia's Megafon; Decries 'Economic Annexation']\n*[https://www.reuters.com/article/marketsNews/idUSMCH62790120080926?sp=true Reuters:Georgia threatens to multiply Russia MegaFon fine]\n*[https://www.reuters.com/article/email/idUSTRE4925D120081003 Reuters: Georgia files charges against Russia's MegaFon]\n*[https://archive.today/20130104130745/http://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS147417+02-Oct-2008+PRN20081002 Reuters: Megafon Goes to Court in Georgia over Disputed South Ossetia Operations]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081028174147/http://www.eurasianet.org/departments/insightb/articles/eav102308b.shtml EurasiaNet: THE FIGHT BETWEEN TBILISI AND MOSCOW OVER SOUTH OSSETIA GOES CELLULAR]\n*[https://archive.today/20130105155236/http://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS177793+16-Dec-2008+PRN20081216 Reuters: Court Upholds Fine Against Megafon for Illegal Operations in Georgia]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/jan/23/russia-alqaida-putin-bin-laden Guardian: Dreams of empire strike back Q: What do Osama bin Laden and Vladimir Putin have in common? A: Worrying ambitions to reverse imperial decline]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110208033744/http://hellomegafon.com/ Unofficial MegaFon page]\n\n{{Russian mobile phone companies}}\n{{Moscow Exchange Index}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Megafon}}\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies of Russia]]\n[[Category:Mobile phone companies of Russia]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Russian brands]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2002]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Moscow Exchange]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toEverton(link changed toEverton F.C.) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MegaFon"}
{"title_page": "Maravarman Rajasimha I", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| reign           = ''c.'' 730 - 765 AD<ref>Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1958, second ed.) ''A History of South India from Prehistoric Times to the Fall of Vijayanagar''. Madras, Oxford University Press. 165.</ref>\n| coronation      =  \n| predecessor     = [[Kochadaiyan Ranadhiran|Ko Chadaiyan Ranadhira]]\n| successor       = Jatila Parantaka Nedunjadaiyan/Varaguna I\n| dynasty         = [[Pandyan dynasty|Pandya]]\n| father          = [[Kochadaiyan Ranadhiran|Ko Chadaiyan Ranadhira]]\n}}\n{{Pandyan}}\n'''Maravarman Rajasimha I''' (''r. c.'' 730 - 765 AD), also known as '''Pallavabhanjana''', was a [[Pandya dynasty|Pandya]] king of early medieval south India.<ref>Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1958, second ed.) ''A History of South India from Prehistoric Times to the Fall of Vijayanagar''. Madras, Oxford University Press. 165.</ref> He was the son and successor of [[Kochadaiyan Ranadhiran|Ko Chadaiyan Ranadhira]].<ref name=\":0\">Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1929) ''The Pandyan Kingdom.'' London, Luzac and Company. 56-58.</ref> He remembered for his important successes against the [[Pallava dynasty|Pallavas]] and in the Kongu country.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAlthough mentioned in the Larger Sinnamanur Plates, the Velvikkudi Grant is the major source of information about this Pandya king.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\">Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1929) ''The Pandyan Kingdom.''London, Luzac and Company. 51-52.</ref> \n\n==Life and career==\n\n=== Siege of Nandigrama ===\nWhen the [[Pallava dynasty|Pallava]] king [[Paramesvaravarman II|Parameswara II]] died in a battle with the Gangas, a crisis arose in the Pallava kingdom over succession. The Pallava officials then chose a young prince, [[Nandivarman II|Nandivarman II Pallavamalla]], ''r. c''. 731 - 96 AD, as the next monarch.<ref>Noburu Karashima (ed.), ''A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations.'' New Delhi: Oxford University Press, 2014. 87-88.</ref> Rajasimha espoused the cause of a son of Parameswara II (named Chitramaya) in this crisis.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nThe Pandya seems to have taken part in the campaigns which led to the siege of [[Nandivarman II]] in Nandigrama (Nandipuram, Kumbakonam) by the Tamil princess. <ref name=\":0\" /> The Velvikkudi Grant ascribes him victories at Neduvayal, Kurumadai, Mannikuricchi (Mannaikkudi<ref name=\":4\" />), Tirumangai, Puvalur, and Kodumbalur.<ref name=\":0\" /> The grant also says that he defeated [[Nandivarman II]] in a battle at Kuzhumbur.<ref name=\":0\" /> The siege was eventually raised by Pallava general Udayachandra (as mentioned in the Udayendiram Plates of Pallavamalla).<ref name=\":0\" /> He defeated the Pandyas, beheaded prince Chitramaya, and made the Pallava throne secure for Nandivarman II.<ref name=\":3\">Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1958, second ed.) ''A History of South India from Prehistoric Times to the Fall of Vijayanagar''. Madras, Oxford University Press. 149-50.</ref> \n\nEven after defeating the Gangas in c. 760 AD, the Pallavas were unable to restrain the growing power of the Pandyas.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Kongu country ===\nRajasimha I won a battle at Periyalur, then crossed the [[Kaveri River]] to subjugate the country of Mala Kongam (borders of Trichy and Thanjavur districts).<ref name=\":1\">Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1929) ''The Pandyan Kingdom.''London, Luzac and Company. 57-58.</ref> The Malava king who suffered defeat gave his daughter in marriage to Rajasimha. It seems that the conquests of the Pandya extended up to Pandikkodumudi (Kodumudi). <ref name=\":1\" />\n\nRajasimha is reportly to have \"renewed the cities of Kudal, Vanchi and Kozhi\". It is possible that this is a reference to the conquest of the ancient capitals of the Pandyas, the Cheras and the Cholas.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Battle of Venbai ===\nVelvikkudi Grant describes the Pandya foray in to the Ganga kingdom (a vassal of the Chalukyas).<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> It says that the Western Chalukya king was defeated by the Pandya king in a battle at Venbai. Subsequently, a Ganga princess was offered in marriage to a Pandya prince (a son of the Pandya king).<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The Western Chalukya king who was defeated was probably Kirttivarman II (and thus the southern territory of the Chalukya kingdom was lost to the Pandyas under Kirttivarman II).<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">Noburu Karashima (ed.), ''A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations.'' New Delhi: Oxford University Press, 2014. 88.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rajasimha, Maravarman, I}}\n[[Category:Pandyan kings]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:8th-century Indian monarchs]]\n\n\n{{India-royal-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| reign           = ''c.'' 730 - 765 AD<ref>Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1958, second ed.) ''A History of South India from Prehistoric Times to the Fall of Vijayanagar''. Madras, Oxford University Press. 165.</ref>\n| coronation      =  \n| predecessor     = [[Kochadaiyan Ranadhiran|Ko Chadaiyan Ranadhira]]\n| successor       = Jatila Parantaka Nedunjadaiyan/Varaguna I\n| dynasty         = [[Pandyan dynasty|Pandya]]\n| father          = [[Kochadaiyan Ranadhiran|Ko Chadaiyan Ranadhira]]\n}}\n{{Pandyan}}\n'''Maravarman Rajasimha I''' (''r. c.'' 730 - 765 AD), also known as '''Pallavabhanjana''', was a [[Pandya dynasty|Pandya]] king of early medieval south India.<ref>Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1958, second ed.) ''A History of South India from Prehistoric Times to the Fall of Vijayanagar''. Madras, Oxford University Press. 165.</ref> He was the son and successor of [[Kochadaiyan Ranadhiran|Ko Chadaiyan Ranadhira]].<ref name=\":0\">Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1929) ''The Pandyan Kingdom.'' London, Luzac and Company. 56-58.</ref> He remembered for his important successes against the [[Pallava dynasty|Pallavas]] and in the Kongu country.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAlthough mentioned in the Larger Sinnamanur Plates, the Velvikkudi Grant is the major source of information about this Pandya king.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\">Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1929) ''The Pandyan Kingdom.''London, Luzac and Company. 51-52.</ref> \n\n==Life and career==\n\n=== Siege of Nandigrama ===\nWhen the [[Pallava dynasty|Pallava]] king [[Paramesvaravarman II|Parameswara II]] died in a battle with the Gangas, a crisis arose in the Pallava kingdom over succession. The Pallava officials then chose a young prince, [[Nandivarman II|Nandivarman II Pallavamalla]], ''r. c''. 731 - 96 AD, as the next monarch.<ref>Noburu Karashima (ed.), ''A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations.'' New Delhi: Oxford University Press, 2014. 87-88.</ref> Rajasimha espoused the cause of a son of Parameswara II (named Chitramaya) in this crisis.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nThe Pandya seems to have taken part in the campaigns which led to the seige of [[Nandivarman II]] in Nandigrama (Nandipuram, Kumbakonam) by the Tamil princess. <ref name=\":0\" /> The Velvikkudi Grant ascribes him victories at Neduvayal, Kurumadai, Mannikuricchi (Mannaikkudi<ref name=\":4\" />), Tirumangai, Puvalur, and Kodumbalur.<ref name=\":0\" /> The grant also says that he defeated [[Nandivarman II]] in a battle at Kuzhumbur.<ref name=\":0\" /> The seige was eventually raised by Pallava general Udayachandra (as mentioned in the Udayendiram Plates of Pallavamalla).<ref name=\":0\" /> He defeated the Pandyas, beheaded prince Chitramaya, and made the Pallava throne secure for Nandivarman II.<ref name=\":3\">Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1958, second ed.) ''A History of South India from Prehistoric Times to the Fall of Vijayanagar''. Madras, Oxford University Press. 149-50.</ref> \n\nEven after defeating the Gangas in c. 760 AD, the Pallavas were unable to restrain the growing power of the Pandyas.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Kongu country ===\nRajasimha I won a battle at Periyalur, then crossed the [[Kaveri River]] to subjugate the country of Mala Kongam (borders of Trichy and Thanjavur districts).<ref name=\":1\">Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1929) ''The Pandyan Kingdom.''London, Luzac and Company. 57-58.</ref> The Malava king who suffered defeat gave his daughter in marriage to Rajasimha. It seems that the conquests of the Pandya extended up to Pandikkodumudi (Kodumudi). <ref name=\":1\" />\n\nRajasimha is reportly to have \"renewed the cities of Kudal, Vanchi and Kozhi\". It is possible that this is a reference to the conquest of the ancient capitals of the Pandyas, the Cheras and the Cholas.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Battle of Venbai ===\nVelvikkudi Grant describes the Pandya foray in to the Ganga kingdom (a vassal of the Chalukyas).<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> It says that the Western Chalukya king was defeated by the Pandya king in a battle at Venbai. Subsequently, a Ganga princess was offered in marriage to a Pandya prince (a son of the Pandya king).<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The Western Chalukya king who was defeated was probably Kirttivarman II (and thus the southern territory of the Chalukya kingdom was lost to the Pandyas under Kirttivarman II).<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">Noburu Karashima (ed.), ''A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations.'' New Delhi: Oxford University Press, 2014. 88.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rajasimha, Maravarman, I}}\n[[Category:Pandyan kings]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:8th-century Indian monarchs]]\n\n\n{{India-royal-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Vanisaac", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correcting spelling: seige->siege", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maravarman_Rajasimha_I"}
{"title_page": "Mega Millions", "text_new": "{{Infobox lottery\n|name        = Mega Millions\n|native_name = \n|native_name_lang = \n|image       = Mega Millions Lottery logo.svg\n|alt         = \n|caption     = \n|region      = [[United States]]\n\n|launch_date = {{Start date|2002|05|17|mf=yes}}<ref name=patch>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/ohio/cleveland/largest-mega-millions-jackpot-history-868-million|title=Mega Millions Winning Numbers For Oct. 19: $1 Billion Jackpot|last=Mosby|first=Chris|website=[[Patch Media|Patch.com]]|date=October 17, 2018|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref>\n|final_date  = \n|operator    = Mega Millions Group<ref name=wp2018>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2018/10/17/mega-millions-tweaked-odds-create-monster-jackpots-it-worked/|title=How Mega Millions changed the odds to create a record-breaking $1.6 billion jackpot|last=Horton|first=Alex|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=October 21, 2018|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref>\n|chief       = \n|regulator   = \n|legislation = \n|highest     = $1.537 billion<ref name=cbcnews2018 />\n|odds        = 302,575,350 to 1 (Mega Millions)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abc7news.com/finance/mega-million-winning-numbers-drawn-for-$1-billion-jackpot/4521117/|title=Mega Million winning numbers drawn for $1 billion jackpot|publisher=[[ABC News]]|date=October 20, 2018|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref>\n|games       = \n|broadcaster = [[WSB-TV]]\n[[People's Television Network]]\n[[RTM]]\n[[TVRI]]\n[[RTB]]\n[[LGTN]]\n[[Vietnam Television]]\n|url         = {{URL|https://www.megamillions.com}}\n}}\n'''Mega Millions''' (which began as '''''The Big Game''''' in 1996 and renamed, temporarily, to '''''The Big Game Mega Millions''''' six years later) is an American multi-jurisdictional [[lottery game]]; as of January 30, 2020, it is offered in 45 states, the District of Columbia, and the U.S. Virgin Islands. The first ''(The Big Game) Mega Millions'' drawing was in 2002; see below. What is now Mega Millions initially was offered in six states; the logo for all versions of the game following the retirement of ''The Big Game'' name featured a gold-colored ball with six stars to represent the game's initial membership, although some lotteries insert their respective logo in the ball.\n\nMega Millions is drawn at 11 p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Time]] on Tuesday and Friday evenings, Tuesday Thursday And Saturday \nEvening is including holidays.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/mega-millions-results-numbers-40-million-jackpot-tuesday-last-night-1352478|title=Mega Millions Results, Numbers for 3/5/19: Did Anyone Win the $40 Million Jackpot on Tuesday (Last) Night?|last=Perez|first=Maria|work=[[Newsweek]]|date=March 6, 2019|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref> Mega Millions is administered by a consortium of its 12 original lotteries;<ref name=MMHomeMedia>{{cite web|url=http://www.megamillions.com/media-center |title=Mega Millions Official Home |publisher=Megamillions.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-17}}</ref> the drawings are held at the studios of [[WSB-TV]] in Atlanta, Georgia, supervised by the [[Georgia Lottery]].<refname=atlanta2018>{{cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/news/local/why-mega-millions-dreams-will-come-true-atlanta-studio/zFQYmv8ZujMtHzwNLg5W9J/|title=Why $1.6B Mega Millions dreams will come true in an Atlanta TV studio|last=Brash|first=Ben|newspaper=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=October 22, 2018|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nUnder the current version's regulations (which began on Saturday October 28 with the first drawing Tuesday October 31) for Mega Millions, the minimum Mega Millions advertised [[Progressive jackpot|jackpot]] is $40&nbsp;million, paid in 30 graduated yearly installments, increasing 5&nbsp;percent each year (unless the cash option is chosen; see below for differences by lotteries on cash/annuity choice regulations.) The jackpot increases when there is no top-prize winner.<ref name=wp2018 />\n\nReflecting common practice among American [[lottery|lotteries]], the jackpot is advertised as a [[nominal value]] of annual installments. A cash value option (the usual choice), when chosen by a jackpot winner, pays the approximate [[present value]] of the installments. Mega Millions' previous format began on October 19, 2013; its first drawing was three days later. The current version of Mega Millions requires players to match 5 of 70 white balls, \nMatch 10 Of 95 withe balls ''and'' the gold-colored \"MegaBall\" from a second field, of 25 numbers ( \nField, Of 49 Numbers( {{nowrap|5/70}} / {{nowrap|1/25}} ).\n\n{{Nowrap|10/95}}) \n{{Nowrap|3/49})\n\nEach game costs $2. Of the 47\nEach game costs PHP 10\nEach game costs RM 5\nEach game costs RP 10,000\nEach game costs SGD 5\nEach game costs 10 Mega Millions jurisdictions, all but California offer an option, called ''Megaplier'' (plays with the ''Megaplier'' are $3 each) where non-jackpot prizes are multiplied by 2, 3, 4, or 5. The \nJackpot prize Ate multiplied \nBy 2, 3, 4, 5, 10, or 100, ''Megaplier'' was made available to all Mega Millions jurisdictions in January 2011; it began as an option available only in Texas.\nSeveral of the game's members offer the ''Just the Jackpot'' option, in which two plays cost $3.\njackpot can be won; none of the lower-tier prizes are available on such a wager.<ref name=CBS636M>{{cite web\n| url = https://www.cbsnews.com/news/2-winning-tickets-in-636-million-mega-millions-drawing/\n| title = 2 winning tickets in $636M Mega Millions drawing - \n| accessdate = 2013-12-18 | date = 2013-12-18| publisher = [[CBS News]] with contributions from [[Associated Press]]\n}}</ref><ref name=MM648M>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.megamillions.com/news-releases/historic-mega-jackpot-split-by-two-tickets\n| title = Historic mega-jackpot split by two tickets\n| accessdate = 2013-12-19 | date = 2013-12-18| publisher = Mega Millions\n}}</ref>\n\nThe largest jackpot (in which the jackpot was ''won'') in Mega Millions history was $1.537 billion, for the October 23, 2018 drawing, in which there was one winning jackpot ticket, sold in [[South Carolina]].<ref name=cbcnews2018 /> The winner anonymously claimed the prize in March 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsbradio.com/news/mega-millions-winner-claims-billion-prize/7mjfu0jRvIim9x3PSgXNnO/|title=Mega Millions winner claims $1.5 billion prize|last=D'Angelo|first=Bob|publisher=[[WSB (AM)]]|date=March 5, 2019|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== The 2010 expansion of Mega Millions and Powerball ==\n[[File:Mega Millions lottery tickets.JPG|thumb|Mega Millions lottery tickets from New Jersey (left) and New York (right); see below for rule variations among the game's 46 members, including which lotteries offer the ''Just the Jackpot'' option]]\nOn October 13, 2009, the Mega Millions consortium and [[Multi-State Lottery Association]] (MUSL) reached an agreement in principle to cross-sell Mega Millions and [[Powerball]] in American lottery jurisdictions, with the two groups referred to as the \"Mega Power Lottery\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldlottery.net/mega-power-lottery.asp |title=Mega Power Lottery |publisher=Worldlottery.net |date= |accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref> by many users. The expansion occurred on January 31, 2010, as 23 Powerball members began selling Mega Millions tickets for their first drawing on February 2, 2010; likewise, 10 Mega Millions members began selling Powerball tickets for their first drawing the next day. [[Montana]] (joining Mega Millions on March 1, 2010) was the first jurisdiction to add either game after the cross-sell expansion. [[Nebraska]] (March 20, 2010), [[Oregon]] (March 28, 2010), [[Arizona]] (April 18, 2010), [[Maine]] (May 9, 2010), [[Colorado]] and [[South Dakota]] (the latter two on May 16, 2010) also have joined Mega Millions since the expansion.\n\nAs of January 2020, there were 47 lotteries offering Mega Millions ''and'' Powerball; Florida joined Mega Millions in May 2013. (Puerto Rico, whose lottery began in the 1930s, currently does not offer Mega Millions.) Mississippi began selling lottery tickets in 2019; it joined Mega Millions on January 30, 2020.\n\nBefore the agreement, the only stores which sold Mega Millions ''and'' Powerball tickets were retailers whose business was on a border between jurisdictions which sold competing games.\n\nThe current Mega Millions format began in October 2017. Plays are $2 per game. For an additional $1 per play, the ''Megaplier'', if activated, multiplies non-jackpot prizes. Multipliers are 2x, 3x, 4x, and 5x (a second-prize Megaplier play can win $5 million cash.) The Megaplier is not available in California, or on ''Just the Jackpot'' wagers (where offered.)<ref>http://www.megamillions.com/how-to-play</ref>\n\n== Current Mega Millions members ==\n[[File:stateswithlotto.png|thumb|400px|As of January 30, 2020, Mega Millions is available in 45 states and the [[District of Columbia]] (''in blue''), plus the [[U.S. Virgin Islands]] ''(not shown)''.]]\n\nMega Millions replaced ''The Big Game'' in 2002 (see below for the evolution of the name ''Mega Millions'').\n\n== Mega Millions and Powerball ==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Lottery \n!Powerball\n!Mega Millions\n|-\n|[[Arizona Lottery|Arizona]]\n|{{dts|April 4, 1994}}\n|{{dts|April 18, 2010}}\n|-\n|[[Arkansas Scholarship Lottery|Arkansas]]\n|{{dts|October 31, 2009}}\n|{{dts|January 31, 2010}}\n|-\n|[[California State Lottery|California]]\n|{{dts|April 8, 2013}}\n|{{dts|June 22, 2005}}\n|-\n|[[Connecticut Lottery|Connecticut]]\n|{{dts|November 28, 1995}}\n|{{dts|January 31, 2010}}\n|-\n|[[Colorado Lottery|Colorado]]\n|{{dts|August 2, 2001}}\n|{{dts|May 16, 2010}}\n|-\n|[[Delaware Lottery|Delaware]]\n|{{dts|January 14, 1991}}\n|{{dts|January 31, 2010}}\n|-\n|[[D.C. Lottery|District of Columbia]]\n|{{dts|February 13, 1988}}\n|{{dts|January 31, 2010}}\n|-\n|[[Florida Lottery|Florida]]\n|{{dts|January 4, 2009}}\n|{{dts|May 15, 2013}}\